<HEADLINE> Abitibi Strike Expected to End This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The five-month strike at
Abitibi-Consolidated Inc., the world's largest newsprint producer,
could end this week after a tentative agreement was reached
between the company and its workers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was struck at the weekend, is expected to
be voted on by the workers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The approval is likely to put an end to the strike that has
stopped production at 10 Abitibi mills in eastern Canada,
according to Monday's Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts have predicted that the end of the strike
will also depress newsprint prices.
</P>
<P>
More than half of newsprint production at Abitibi has been shut
down by the strike, offsetting downward pressure on prices caused
by weak demand in Asia, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Company and union officials refused to release details of the
tentative agreement. But sources told the paper that the deal
calls for a six-year contract and an annual wage increase of two
percent.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be less than what the union had been
seeking. The strike, which began on June 15, was over demands for
six percent pay increases this year as well as in 1999 and 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
