<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for Lifting of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 16 (Xinhua) -- "It is about time" to lift the
U.N. economic sanctions on Iraq, visiting Russian Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak on the latest Iraq-U.N. standoff, Sergeyev also
urged progress by the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in its
mission of disarming Iraq of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Seeing no hope to have the sanctions lifted, Iraq halted the
dealings with UNSCOM last month, prompting U.S. threats of
military strikes against it.
</P>
<P>
In an about-face, Iraq decided Saturday to resume cooperation
with UNSCOM and narrowly averted U.S. military strikes.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions imposed on Iraq by the U.N. Security Council
after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait will not be lifted until UNSCOM
certifies Iraq has destroyed its nuclear, chemical and biological
weapons as well as the long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said Russia is opposed to military solution to the
Iraqi issue, but it also criticizes Baghdad's halt of cooperation
with the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The Russian minister arrived here Sunday for a three-day visit
after a trip to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said he conveyed a message during the meeting to
Mubarak from Russian President Boris Yeltsin on bilateral ties and
other issues of common interest.
</P>
<P>
The meeting touched on cooperation in the military and economic
fields, he said, adding his visit is in part aimed at preparations
for Yeltsin's visit to Egypt planned for early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
