<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Suspends West Bank Troop Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu announced on Monday the suspension of troops
withdrawal from the West Bank unless the Palestinians cancel their
plans to announce a statehood next May.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking in the Knesset (parliament) at the start of the
debate on the approval of the Wye River agreement signed with the
Palestinians under which Israel will withdraw troops from 13
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after a continuous war of rhetoric in
which Israel and the Palestinians accuse each other of hindering
the implementation of the agreement signed in Washington last
month.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Israel should have begun to
withdraw its troops Monday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed a vow on Sunday to declare an independent
Palestinian state on May 4, 1999, when the five-year interim
period under the Oslo accords expires, and warned Israel that "our
rifle is ready."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he does not intend to implement any withdrawal
"unless things are corrected in public."
</P>
<P>
He said his cabinet will convene on Wednesday to review the
suspension of the troops pullback. 
</P>
</TEXT>
