<HEADLINE> UK Official Discloses Previous Strike Warning Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking official of the
United Kingdom confirmed Monday that Britain had sent a private
warning to Iraq last Thursday that it would carry out air strikes
unless Baghdad complied with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We did issue a warning to the Iraqis privately on Thursday
that this was going to happen, a very considerable strike," Prime
Minister Tony Blair's official spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said Blair also planned to tell parliament on Monday
afternoon that if President Saddam Hussein obstructed the work of
U.N. weapons inspectors again "there will be a strike without
warning".
</P>
<P>
Before Baghdad promised to cooperate unconditionally with the
U.N. arms inspectors, Blair had given orders to Royal Air Force
Tornado jets stationed in Kuwait to prepar to strike Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Tornados would have joined U.S. bombers in a strike, but
President Clinton canceled the attack when he received word that
Saddam was backing down.
</P>
<P>
Blair is scheduled to speak with President Clinton again on
Monday afternoon to discuss the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, Blair said Britain would maintain the force of
jet-bombers now stationed in Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
