<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Step Up Administrative Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Stepping up administrative
reform was considered as one of the major measures taken by the
government to achieve the targets of socio-economic development
set for 1999, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
VNA said "administrative reform is an issue of primary concern
of most national assembly deputies. They have said that this
reform is both slow and not yet efficient."
</P>
<P>
In his report at the current session of the National Assembly,
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai said that public agencies have still
shown bureaucratic expressions in conducting public affairs and
that they should be responsible for their weaknesses and quickly
improve their conduct of public affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to Pham Si Danh, chief of the Office of the Ministry
of Finance, the ministry is focusing on reforming administrative
policies, the administrative apparatus, and administrative
procedures.
</P>
<P>
Do Que Luong, deputy governor of the state bank, said that the
aim of the administrative reform in the banking sector is to
ensure rapidity and convenience in dealing with customers and safe
protection of public funds.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh city's authorities
are stepping up the administrative reform in many fields,
according to VNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
