<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Red Cross Conference Opens in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The fifth Asia-Pacific regional
conference of red cross and red crescent societies opened here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
As many as 165 representatives in 44 delegations from
Asian-Pacific and Middle East countries, donor countries and
international organizations are attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference focuses discussions on ways, solutions and
resources to provide assistance in health care and education to
victims of natural calamities and the regional monetary-financial
crisis, particularly old people, disadvantaged children and
families having high numbers of jobless members.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference, Vietnam's Vice State President
Nguyen Thi Binh said the international federation of red cross and
red crescent societies with its noble humanitarian target of all
for natural calamity victims, poor people and orphans, has made
great contributions to helping people in many countries including
Vietnam over the past years.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis in the region has negatively affected
Vietnam's economy. Vietnam together with other regional countries
will still face many challenges and difficulties in 1999, Mrs.
Binh said.
</P>
<P>
She said Vietnam has to continue overcoming serious aftermath
left over by the wars, hence the country is striving to mobilize
internal strength, continue with the renovation process, and
gradually improve the cultural and material life of the people.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first of its kind to be held in Vietnam,
will last until Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
