<HEADLINE> Iran, Finland Agree on Closer Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Finland have agreed on
stepping up their cooperation on regional and international
issues, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen and her
Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharazi discussed the ways to enhance
the Tehran-Helsinki relations in political, economic, trade,
scientific, telecommunications and environment fields.
</P>
<P>
They also called for furthering cooperation between the
European Union (EU) and the Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC) on various fields, including campaigns against terrorism and
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Finland will assume the rotating EU presidency for the second
half of 1998 and will become a member of the EU Troika in
1999. Iran is the current chairman of the OIC.
</P>
<P>
Halonen called for avoiding double taxation between the two
countries and encouraging joint investment projects to boost trade
exchanges with Iran.
</P>
<P>
She proposed exchanges of data and holding seminars on
scientific, technical and environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Halonen expressed satisfaction over the positive trend in the
EU-Iran relations and the hope that EU-Iran comprehensive dialog
will continue under Finland's presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish minister, who arrived here on Sunday for a two-day
official visit, said that Helsinki welcomes the proposal put
forward by Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on dialogs among
different civilizations and cultures.
</P>
<P>
Kharazi, on his part, noted the potentials of their bilateral
economic cooperation, saying the current trade exchanges between
the two countries falls short of the economic capacity of Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister urged central banks, chambers of commerce
of the two countries and Iran-Finland joint economic commission to
explore ways to facilitate bilateral trade and transactions.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the OIC and the EU will lead to
understanding and cooperation, he said, adding that Iran is ready
to cooperate with the EU in different grounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
