<HEADLINE> China's Aviation Administration Predicts Market Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The '98 China International Air
Show, which opened on Sunday, has brought Boeing, Airbus,
BMW-Rolls Royce, Daimler-Benz, and many other big companies to the
southern city of Zhuhai, Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Civil Aviation Administration of China
(CAAC) says this is a proof that they are optimistic about China's
aviation market. CAAC estimates that air transport will grow at an
annual rate of 10 percent over the next two decades and will need
another 600 airplanes.
</P>
<P>
The two largest aircraft producers in the world, Boeing and
Airbus, have also shown confidence in China's market. In a market
report published earlier this year, Boeing said it expects to see
the world's fastest annual air transportation growth in China, at
9.5 percent, and the market expansion will mean the purchase of
1,800 planes, valued at 125 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A similar forecast was made by Airbus, Boeing's major
competitor. Annual growth in the Chinese market will be 6.8
percent in the next 20 years, compared with 5.1 percent in the
rest of the world, and 1,300 passenger planes will be needed.
</P>
<P>
Airbus had 11 aircraft on display at the show, which it is
either manufacturing or developing, with the A340-600 being
showcased.
</P>
<P>
Boeing had a new image at the show after the merger with
McDonnnell Douglas. Its focus was on the Boeing 717-200. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
