<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nitrous Oxide Found in Tropical Waters of Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from the
University of Hawaii have discovered large amounts of nitrous
oxide -- also known as laughing gas -- in tropical waters of the
Pacific, the Washington Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It has been known that marine bacteria manufacture nitrous
oxide in the deepest parts of the ocean. But two researchers from
the university found the gas in shallower waters, and at much
higher levels than previously known.
</P>
<P>
Based on the finding, the researchers estimate that the world's
oceans release six million tons of the gas into atmosphere each
year, three times more than projected.
</P>
<P>
Nitrous oxide, known as laughing gas, contributes to the global
warming as well as the destruction of the ozone, thus scientists
worry it may exacerbate environmental problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
