<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Suspends West Bank Troop Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu announced on Monday that he is suspending
troops withdrawal from the West Bank unless the Palestinians
retract the statements declaring independence next May.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking in the Knesset (parliament) at the start of the
two-day debate on the approval of the Wye River agreement signed
with the Palestinians under which Israel will withdraw troops from
13 percent of the West Bank within 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I do not intend to implement any withdrawal under these
circumstance, under the threats that Arafat made yesterday, until
these things are corrected publicly and unequivocably," Netanyahu
said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the statements made by Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, who renewed his
vow Sunday to declare an independent Palestinian state on May 4
and warned Israel that the Palestinians would take their guns if
prevented by Israel from praying in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that Jerusalem "has been, is and always be
the capital of Israel and only the capital of Israel."
</P>
<P>
He said he would convene his cabinet Wednesday to review the
suspension of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Palestinian news agency Wafa said that Arafat's
statements were "misunderstood," noting that the PNA is committed
to the path of peace.
</P>
<P>
Before Netanyahu made the announcement, Palestinian Negotiator
Hassan Asfour accused the Israeli prime minister of trying to
evade his obligations, urging Netanyahu to stop using excuses.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Netanyahu had called on Arafat to seek
clarifications before the start of the parliament debate to seek
clarification.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have indicated that Arafat's renewal of
his pledge to declare an independent state came as a response to
Netanyahu's earlier annexation threats and as an expression of
frustration over Israel's delay in carrying out the redeployment
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The first substantial act for Israel to implement the
agreement had been slated for Monday, when Israel should pull
back its troops from 2 percent of the West Bank in the first phase
of a three-stage redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has said it would be delayed for several days.
</P>
</TEXT>
