<HEADLINE> Competitiveness Important for Recovery: HK Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive of
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, Tung Chee
Hwa, said here Monday that the revival of competitiveness is the
most important factor in ensuring economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Economic recovery would be possible if a quick revival of
competitiveness was achieved, Tung said after meeting Singapore
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
Both Tung and Goh are here to attend the sixth informal meeting
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) leaders, which
will be held here Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tung said their main concern was the serious impact of the
financial crisis on Asia and that how best to prevent another
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the Group of Seven (G-7) major industrialized nations
had adopted a policy which was actually proposed by 22 economies
at a meeting in Washington and if the policy was followed,
everyone would benefit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a press release issued by the Hong Kong
delegation, Tung said that he and Goh had discussed APEC's role in
dealing with the financial crisis and the need for Asian input in
any discussions or initiatives to enhance and strengthen
international financial structures.
</P>
<P>
Tung was quoted as saying, "Close cooperation is now more
important than ever if we are to achieve a quick recovery for all
in the current financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
Tung said Hong Kong and Singapore should work together within
APEC to seize every opportunity for an early recovery from the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
APEC, formed in 1989, now has 21 members -- Australia; Brunei;
Canada; Chile; China; Hong Kong, China; Indonesia; Japan; South
Korea; Malaysia; Mexico; New Zealand; Papua New Guinea; Peru; the
Philippines; Russia; Singapore; Chinese Taipei; Thailand; the
United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
