<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Aid for Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
voiced a proposal Monday that its Council of Ministers authorize
exceptional balance-of-payments aid to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the EU's executive body, said the assistance,
which could amount to a maximum of 60 million ECU (57 million US
dollars), will take the form of a combination of grants and loans.
</P>
<P>
The aid will serve as part of the EU strategy to promote the
peace process there and the transition of Bosnia to a market
economy, it added.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silgy said the time had come "to
go beyond the objective of reconstruction and focus increased
attention on the structural reforms which will make it possible to
foster growth and creation".
</P>
<P>
"Promoting the development of the private sector and
job-creation is necessary to find a medium-term solution to the
problem of refugees and displaced persons," he said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also noted that significant progress had been
made in recent months in setting up the central institutions and
introducing the legislation that were essential to the functioning
of a unified economy in the two entities of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The EU aid will, in particular, facilitate the implementation
of a consistent macro-economic program and speed up the structural
reforms, including development of the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
