<HEADLINE> More Rural Homes in Zimbabwe Get Solar Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The global environmental
facility (GEF) Monday said a total of 12,000 solar systems had
been installed in rural areas in Zimbabwe by October this year.
</P>
<P>
The project funded by the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) was officially terminated in June, but work went on due to
increased demand.
</P>
<P>
Project manager Gibson Mandishona said they managed to beat
the targeted figure of 9,000 installations in rural homes,
clinics, schools and business centers.
</P>
<P>
The GEF project started in 1993 as a pilot project to reduce
the problem of global pollution by substituting solar energy for
fuels such as candles and paraffin.
</P>
<P>
He told the Zimbabwe News Agency (Ziana) that consultants were
now working on a successor project expected to start early next
year.
</P>
<P>
Mandishona said the project which emphasize the importance of
environmental protection and poverty alleviation would also
address other forms of renewable energy programs which included
wind and biogas.
</P>
<P>
''My hope is that if a new project takes place it should
drastically improve the coverage of solar home systems,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
''The successor project, if accomplished, will solidly put
Zimbabwe on a worldwide renewable energy map,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was envisaged that renewable energies were the hope
for the future because they abated global warming and
environmental stress.
</P>
<P>
''Zimbabwe could lead the Southern African Development
Community region into the era of modern renewable energy,'' he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
