<HEADLINE> U.N. Staff Leave Amman for Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Some 150 United Nations
humanitarian workers left here Monday for Baghdad to resume their
tasks in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The return came two days after Iraq agreed to unconditionally
resume cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors and the United States
temporally withdrew its military menace.
</P>
<P>
About 120 of the U.N. workers departured on four Iraqi buses
and will travel about 12 hours and some 500 kilometers through the
desert before arriving in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Hours later, another 30 U.N. staff, mainly senior workers, left
on a U.N. plane sent from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
They were evacuated from Baghdad to Amman on November 12 for
fear of possible U.S. air strikes to compel Iraq to reverse its
decision made on October 31 to halt all cooperation with the
U.N. Special Commission for disarming Iraq. 
</P>
