<HEADLINE> 190 Houses Destroyed, 750 Homeless in SA Tornado </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The tornado that swept
through Harrismith, a city 300 km southeast of Johannesburg, on
Sunday, destroyed about 190 houses and left 750 people homeless,
South African Press Association reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The homeless, most of them from the Intabazwe township, would
be sheltered at the Harrismith show-grounds, said Corlea Harold,
speaking on behalf of the Harrismith Town Council.
</P>
<P>
Police and rescue workers are helping people move their
belongings to the show-grounds Monday afternoon, Harold said,
adding that a special committee had been established to provide
food for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
Of the 15 people admitted to Harrismith Hospital on Sunday,
only three were still receiving treatment. One patient was in a
serious condition, Harold said.
</P>
<P>
According to Harrismith officials, it would take about one
week and millions of Rand to repair the damage and restore
electricty. Currently one U.S. Dollar equals 5.8 Rand.
</P>
<P>
Eskom, the national electricity utility of South Africa, said
it would be deploying extra man-power to restore electricity in
the tornado-torn area as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
