<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Slips in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial
production at the nation's factories, mines and utilities slipped
in October, the fourth decline in five months, the Federal Reserve
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the Federal Reserve's industrial production index fell
a seasonally adjusted 0.1 percent. Utility output dropped 3.4
percent. Demand for electricity had been at elevated levels over
the Summer but then dipped again as temperatures returned to more
normal levels. Production at mines and oil wells fell 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, output at factories rose 0.3 percent, showing partly
rebound from a 0.6 percent drop in September, according to the
Fed report.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production dropped despite the fact that
manufacturing in October was buoyed by a 2.9 percent increase in
automotive products and gains for appliances, computers, furniture
and construction supplies. That helped offset drops for farm and
industrial equipment.
</P>
<P>
The slight drop in overall industrial output helped lower the
industrial operating rate to 80.6 percent of capacity, from 81
percent in September. Factories operated at 79.4 percent of their
capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
