<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-16 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Accused of Lacking Desire for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) on Monday accused Israel
of lacking "sincere desire" to establish peace with its Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa,
head of PLO Political Department Farouq Qaddoumi said that Israel
has escaped the commitments to the land-for-peace principle
determined in the 1991 Mideast peace conference in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Qaddoumi termed the Palestinian-Israeli Wye deal as "a security
agreement," other than a peace agreement, which he said will lead
the Middle East peace process to "a dangerous crisis."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis signed last month in Washington
the deal on Israeli phased withdrawal from another 13 percent of
the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian tough measures against
anti-Israeli violence.
</P>
<P>
Qaddoumi said that he was, for the time being, opposed to
revising the Palestinian National Charter calling for destruction
of Israel, as demanded by the Wye deal.
</P>
<P>
He said the charter will be null and void when a new charter or
a constitution is formulated for a future independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
The PLO official denied reports about proposals that a new PLO
be set up, saying there is only one PLO and no request has been
tendered by any of its 10 member-groups to form a new Palestinian
organization.
</P>
<P>
Qaddoumi, a former close comrade of Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, disagrees with Arafat on the strategy for resolving the
Palestinian-Israeli conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
