<HEADLINE> UNITA Rearming forces: Ex-officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has got "many weapons" in the past
four years and its chairman Jonas Savimbi has now had a "well
armed" force, two UNITA ex-officers said in Huambo Monday.
</P>
<P>
Major Mateus Chingaluco "Chinga" and Gervasio Lesawala "Pety"
said when some UNITA troops were disbanding at assembly points
according to the 1994 Lusaka Accord, some others were being
trained in secret bases, such as Jamba in central Huambo
province.
</P>
<P>
The two just escaped from Bailundo, a city controlled by
UNITA, last week. Chinga served as an instructor in a task force
of UNITA, while Pety was an officer commanding the bodyguards of
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
"Renewed civil war tops the most popular topic in the leading
circle within the UNITA region recently," they said, adding,
"Many oppose Savimbi's war policy."
</P>
<P>
The hard-liners who advocate war the most are general Abilio
Camalata, UNITA's secretary general and Altino Sapalalo "Bock",
one of the main generals of the UNITA military forces.
</P>
<P>
They have summoned the demobilized UNITA fighters back,
attempting to grab power for Savimbi through armed force, the two
former UNITA officers said.
</P>
<P>
Many are against a renewed war in Angola, but with
ever-intensifying control, people find it hard to speak out what
they think in their minds in UNITA areas, they said.
</P>
<P>
UNITA is now trying to recruit men for their army throughout
the country on the one hand, and to plunder food and animals for
their logistic supply on the other, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
