<HEADLINE> African Reporters Urged to Cover Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean minister Monday
urged African journalists to giver more coverage to environmental
and developmental issues in their areas.
</P>
<P>
Opening a three-day environment and development workshop here,
Environment and Tourism Deputy Minister Edward Chindori-Chininga
said if African journalists did not take interest in writing
about issues in their countries, there would be no balance in the
north-south information flow.
</P>
<P>
"The constant coverage of environment and development issues
in the media will eventually cultivate a culture that will
promote civic action against all forms of environmental
malpractice," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said some foreign journalists' reports on environmental
management in Africa were "misleading and incorrect."
</P>
<P>
The workshop would focus on the importance of press coverage
of environmental and developmental issues and on how
international environmental conventions impact on trade, resource
use and management.
</P>
<P>
The workshop organized by African resources trust and the
United States information service is being attended by 30
journalists from the southern African region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
