<HEADLINE> Finland, Iran to Hold Gathering on Security, Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Finland and Iran will hold a
joint gathering in Helsinki to discuss issues related to
security, human rights and refugees, visiting Finnish Foreign
Minister Tajra Halonen announced here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of reporters, Halonen said that a group of
academics, diplomats and politicians from both countries will
participate in the gathering. However, she did not give the exact
date.
</P>
<P>
Halonen expressed the hope that representatives from
non-governmental organizations of the two countries can
participate in the gathering, the official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
Problems will not be solved if there is no talk, she said,
adding that Finland, which will be the rotating president of the
European Union (EU) in 1999, will follow up constructive dialog
between the EU and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Undoubtedly, the Finnish minister said, the talks will begin
with general and simple issues and gradually proceeds to cover
more complex issues.
</P>
<P>
She termed Iran as an important country in a complex,
difficult and at the same time interesting region, saying that
Helsinki maintains Tehran can forge regional cooperation and boost
regional relations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Halonen arrived here on Sunday for a two-day official
visit. The two countries will sign two economic agreements at the
end of her visit to Tehran, IRNA added. 
</P>
