<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Performance Improves in Sub-Saharan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Manufacturing industries in
sub-Saharan Africa showed encouraging performance in 1997
although manufacturing value added (MVA) growth fell marginally
from 4.5 percent in 1996 to 4.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. newsletter, Industrial Africa, released to the Zimbabwe
News Agency Monday said adverse weather conditions like droughts
and floods in some parts of the region affected agricultural
output and indirectly the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, political and economic uncertainties continued to
dampen growth," said the newsletter which is published by the
U.N. Industrial Development Organization (Unido).
</P>
<P>
"As in past years, the major economies in the region such as
Cameroun, Nigeria and Zimbabwe all recorded higher MVA growth:
8.4, 2.5 and 5.6 respectively from 7.8, 1.0 and 3.7 percent in
1996," it said.
</P>
<P>
It said increased capital inflows accelerated growth in the
cfa Franc (French-speaking African states) zone at a time
performance in the least developed countries (LDCS) was
discouraging.
</P>
<P>
But during the year more than half of the 33 LDCS in the
sub-Saharan region registered lower MVA growth compared with the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past three years, the total growth of the region has
been above the average annual rate of population growth which is
about three percent.
</P>
<P>
"This has resulted in a corresponding increase in the per
capita income," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, overall economic growth in the long run had been
hampered by economic and political instability, pervasive
poverty, low savings and investment rates, low human capital
endowment and poor infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
It said the region needed to reduce political and economic
uncertainties and improve its infrastructure and human
development in order to attract foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
