<HEADLINE> AIDS to Make Tanzanian Orphans Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of children
orphaned by deadly disease AIDS is rising quickly in Tanzania,
United Children's Fund (UNICEF) said in Dar es Salaam Monday.
</P>
<P>
A consultant with UNICEF office in Dar es Salaam told Xinhua
that the number of children who lost mother or father or both
parents was 200,000 in 1996, but may rise to 800,000 by the end
of this century.
</P>
<P>
The consultant, who declined to be named, said the UNICEF has
collected the information from the National AIDS Control Program.
</P>
<P>
She said UNICEF has been trying to assist the orphans by
keeping them at schools, making them live with extended family
members such as their parent's relatives, and providing health
care and other services.
</P>
<P>
The consultant said it is improper to describe the group of
children as "AIDS orphans," a term which seems to be discriminate
against them.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency has been assisting Tanzania in caring for AIDS
orphans since early 1990s and has promised to provide special
assistance to Bagamoyo, Karagwe and Makete areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
At a recent workshop held in the Kibaha town, some 40
kilometers northwest of Dar es Salaam, government officials
stressed the importance of fighting AIDS to help children.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 million children in the world have one parent or
both parents dead due to the deadly disease AIDS since 1983,
health officials here said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is a country leading in Africa with HIV/AIDS cases.
At least one million people in the country have been infected
with HIV, virus that causes AIDS, statistics indicate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
