<HEADLINE> Profits Fall As British Steel Axes Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- British Steel has warned that
the company would make losses this year as a result of the global
economic crisis, and called for further interest rate cuts to
shore up British business.
</P>
<P>
The company has already cut 1400 jobs over the last six months,
mainly across plants in northern England. BBC quoted BS chairman
Brian Moffatt Monday as saying that there would be more to come as
BC accelerates its job shedding program.
</P>
<P>
The firm announced plans to axe around 1600 staff in the next
six months in the face of the strong pound and falling steel
prices. The cut will be made mostly in the UK.
</P>
<P>
It was also announced here Monday the pre-tax profits in the
six months to October 3 were 108 million pounds - down on 143
million last time.
</P>
<P>
However, the firm said that recent falls in interest rates and
the value of the pound should help it restore competitiveness in
its domestic and export markets over the next year. 
