<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's 600 Plants with Medicinal Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Biodiversity
Conservation and Research Institute of Ethiopia says Monday that
over 600 of the estimated 7,000 species of plants in the country
are known to have medicinal value.
</P>
<P>
Opening here a six-day training workshop on "industrial
exploitation of medicinal and aromatic plants in East Africa",
Director of the Institute Abebe Demissie quotes a recent study as
unveiling that about 45 million rural and urban population of the
country employ many of these species traditional for primary
health care purposes.
</P>
<P>
Abebe says this health care system is "both viable and
culturally integrated for the majority of the population" and
thus is believed to continue into the future.
</P>
<P>
The institute, in collaboration with other sister institutions
and various stake-holders, is developing a comprehensive project
document which puts forth medicinal and aromatic plants,
according to the director.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from East African countries attend the
workshop. 
</P>
