<HEADLINE> Reppas: Ocalan Has Not been Invited to Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece said Monday that Abdulah
Ocalan, the leader of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) currently
under arrest in Italy, had not been invited to Greece and the
Greek government had not received any message from him.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that Athens had no contact with Ocalan or his
representative.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was unaware of reports of a supposed message
from Ocalan to the Greek government being brought by the
Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) parliamentarian Costas
Mandouvas, who arrived in Rome last Saturday to issue Ocalan with
an invitation to visit Athens.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, 109 Greek parliamentarians, including
Mandouvas, signed an invitation for the PKK leader to visit
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that Athens had fought for a political resolution
to the Kurds' long-running separatist cause and against the use of
force by Turkish authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the issue of whether or not Ocalan
received political asylum was "a matter of Italy's leaders and
laws."
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Greece (KKE) and the Coalition of the
Left and Progress supported Ocalan to receive political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Democratic Social Movement leader Dimitris Tsovolas is
expected to meet with Italy's ambassador in Athens to discuss the
asylum issue for Ocalan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
