<HEADLINE> Cohen Says Last Chance for Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Monday that the U.S. military will strike
Iraq without warning if President Saddam Hussein breaks his
promise to cooperate fully with U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
"No more hiding and seeking. No more playing games," Cohen told
reporters at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
"I think that he has had more than sufficient warning. I don't
believe any additional warning is required," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, President Bill Clinton accepted the promise of Iraq
to resume full cooperation with the U.N. inspectors and an
imminent military strike against Iraq was avoided.
</P>
<P>
"I think everyone understands that this is the last go-round as
far as Saddam is concerned. He has had every opportunity to fully
comply. We will see whether the deeds are going to match his
words," Cohen said in response to questions at a swearing-in
ceremony for new Navy Secretary Richard Danzig.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 U.S. warplanes, including 12 F-117A stealth
fighters, that had been en route to the Gulf in a major military
buildup would likely be returned to the United States from
intermediate stops in Europe in the coming days, said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
But he made clear that more than 180 U.S. attack and support
planes will remain in the Gulf region with nearly 20 American
warships.
</P>
<P>
"If we find that Saddam is breaching this agreement, then no
one, anyone, anywhere could fault the United States and our allies
for considering action at that time," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
