<HEADLINE> African Women Suffer From Early Sex: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- World Health Organization
(WHO) country representative in Uganda Habib Njie has said that
engaging in early sex by African women is a major factor to the
spread of cancer of the cervix.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Monday at a national workshop on cancer of
the cervix in Uganda held in Entebbe, 45 kms south of the capital
city Kampala, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
Cervical cancer is now widely accepted as one of the most
common cancers in the world second to cancer of the breast, the
WHO official said.
</P>
<P>
Of the half a million new cases of cervical cancer in the
world, 80 percent of them occur among women living in the
developing countries, the report said. 
</P>
