<HEADLINE> UK Govt Subsidizes Farmers with 120m Pounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government on
Monday unveiled details of a 120 million pound (200 million U.S.
dollars) emergency aid package for farmers who are hit hard by
strong pounds and mad cow disease crisis.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Nick Brown told the House of Commons the
aid was being made available because all farming sectors had been
"adversely affected by a marked deterioration in market
conditions".
</P>
<P>
Brown said the package came as recognition of the "extremely
difficult circumstances" facing the agriculture industry.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture minister confirmed the government intended to
draw 48 million pounds (80 million dollars) in compensation for
cattle farmers from the European Commission for the current year.
</P>
<P>
Brown said, subject to approval from Brussels, Hill Livestock
Compensatory Allowances for 1999 would be increased by 60 million
pounds (100 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Brown also announced a long-term government review of farming,
which he promised would produce "policies which offer a secure
future" for rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The rescue package is intended to counteract the effect of
tumbling farm incomes over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
Farm earnings have fallen 80 percent since 1996, raising the
prospect of thousands of farms going bankrupt with the loss of
many thousands more jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
