<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Iraqis Have Breathing Spell After Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Baghdad on Monday is permeated
with an atmosphere of relaxation following the last-minute U.S.
cancellation of military strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Thank Allah, a military attack by the United States at last
was averted and my business restored today as usual," Abudallah
Razaq, a shoe-store owner in Alawy Street, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Life returned to normal Monday in the capital that had
witnessed demonstrations against U.S. military threats and a rush
of storing fuel and foodstuff during the past week.
</P>
<P>
A possible military attack, triggered by Iraq's suspension of
cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
eliminating weapons of mass destruction in Iraq on October 31, has
been haunting the Iraqis in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
The value of U.S. dollar dropped drastically over the past
24 hours vis-a-vis a rise of the Iraqi dinar's value. One
dollar, which could change for 1,800 dinars on Sunday, dropped
to 1,600 dinars on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At an old neighborhood market in Alawy Street, the price of
tomato was 350 dinars one kilogram, 150 dinars lower than that on
Sunday. The grain price also dropped by 25 percent in the past 24
hours after Iraq decided to allow the U.N. inspectors to resume
their work.
</P>
<P>
An old housewife said she was praying for peace in the past
days. "I am not afraid of death, I was only worried about the
safety of my children and grandchildren." She burst into tears
when hearing the news that Washington had cancelled its military
attacks on Iraq in the last minute.
</P>
<P>
However, some intellectuals hesitated at getting
optimistic as the lifting of the U.N. embargo which was imposed
on Iraq following its invasion of Kuwait in August 1990 is not in
sight.
</P>
<P>
"Although Iraq averted a military attack right now, the
sanctions cannot be lifted before the next century," an Iraqi
reporter said pessimistically.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials and state-controlled news media expressed
anger over U.S. President Bill Clinton's Sunday night speech in
which he encouraged the Iraqi opposition to topple the present
regime in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz Sunday called
Clinton's speech as a "flagrant interference in Iraq's internal
affairs."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Eric Falt, spokesman for the U.N.
Humanitarian Program in Iraq, announced Monday all U.N.
staff, including the weapons inspectors, are expected to return
to Baghdad as of Monday. The first batch, 151 U.N. relief
workers will return to Baghdad later Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had been stepping up its military buildup in the Gulf
for air strikes against Iraqi targets before Baghdad announced to
rescind its decision of non-cooperation with UNSCOM on October
31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
