<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Farmers Steps to Stop Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Ten more commercial farms in
Mashonaland East have been invaded by land hungry villagers,
forcing the owners to seek court orders to curb their illegally
resettling themselves, the Daily Herald reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two such orders have been granted for the protection of farms
in the enterprise area in Mashonaland East province. Among other
instructions in the provisional order, police were ordered to
ensure that the farms would not be invaded and to take any action
necessary to prevent illegal settlements.
</P>
<P>
With police battling to cope with problems at already invaded
farms owing to a shortage of resources and man power, enforcing
the orders has proved a mammoth task for the force.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 families have so far moved onto five farms around the
Juru area in Chikwaka communal area of eastern Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Governor of Mashonaland East David Karimanzira Sunday said the
government was committed to resettling its people and the
national program had already started.
</P>
<P>
"But it is important for people to realize that this is a
five-year program. Everyone cannot be resettled at the same
time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite concerted efforts by both the government and ruling
ZANU (PF) provincial leadership to allow for orderly
resettlement, the invaders have steadfastly refused to vacate the
farms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
