<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, France Coordinate Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bonn, November 16 (Xinhua) -- German and French financial
leaders agreed Monday that their two countries should coordinate
economic and fiscal policies and take a leading role in guiding
the fortunes of the future single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
But the regular semi-annual meeting of the German-French
economic council today did not produce any agreement on ideas
advocated by German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine for
establishing exchange rates between the euro, the dollar and
japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
Both Lafontaine and his French counterpart Strauss-Kahn, after
the German-French economic council meeting today, said to the
press that with the introduction of the euro next January 1, the
situation on financial markets would change and therefore a common
economic and fiscal policy would become necessary.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn called it a "good sign for the euro", that France
and Germany had "very similar opinions on almost all the issues".
While saying there was no agreement yet on Lafontaine's idea of
narrow exchange rate corridors for the euro, dollar and yen, he
added that the two sides would continue to study the idea to find
a common stance.
</P>
<P>
About the exchange rate of Euro, Lafontaine explained that
nobody was striving for a static exchange rates between euro,
dollar and japanese yen. And his idea for narrow fluctuation
corridors was not meant to be carried out in the short-term, but
rather was aimed at finding a "narrowing in real economic terms"
of exchange rates. He said also that the Group of Seven leading
nations should cooperate to achieve more stable exchange rates.
But methods of achieving it could be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Other topics covered in today's German-French meeting included
harmonization of taxes in the E.U. by mid-1999 and the question of
a more balanced distribution of the costs of the E.U.
</P>
<P>
The German-French economic council meeting today was the first
regular council meeting since the new German government took power
in Bonn and the talks were devoted to mapping out policy positions
ahead of next week's European Union finance ministers meeting and
the Franco-German summit at the end of the month in Potsdam.
</P>
</TEXT>
