<HEADLINE> U.N. Arms Inspectors to Resume Work in Iraq on Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A group of 86 U.N. arms
inspectors will return to Baghdad Tuesday on a U.N. flight, and
the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM in charge of
disarming Iraq, is expected to resume its duty on Wednesday, a
U.N. spokesman announced here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, U.N. spokesman, told a press conference that the
weapons inspectors, working with UNSCOM and the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), are scheduled to leave for Baghdad
from Bahrain, where they have been on standby since they left Iraq
last week.
</P>
<P>
"On Wednesday, another six UNSCOM staff will make the same
journey," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sergey, Lavrov, Russian permanent representative to
the United Nations, told reporters here on Monday that UNSCOM
should carry out its duty "properly and exactly according to the
U.N. resolution" and "show respect for Iraqi sovereignty and
dignity of Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Iraq averted air strikes at the last minute on Saturday by
saying it would let the inspectors resume work.
</P>
<P>
Russia, together with China and France, has lashed out at
Richard Butler, who heads UNSCOM, for his withdrawal decision last
week without consultations with Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that he made the decision on "strong
recommendation" from Washington. 
