<HEADLINE> IMF not to Change Position on Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The position taken by the
International Monetary Fund to Russia will be unchanged, the IMF
office in Moscow said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the IMF office in Moscow Martin Gilman said that though
the situation in Russia is too uncertain, the IMF mission is also
to continue talks on the same terms set by the previous mission.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to comment on the possible results of the talks
by the IMF mission which is to arrive here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF told the government earlier this month that the fourth
quarter federal budget deficit must not exceed 50 billion rubles,
and the government should do away with the practice of offsetting
debt.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements reached by IMF and Russia prior to the
government's August 17 decisions, the IMF was to provide 4.3
billion U.S. dollars for Russia in September.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the office of the World Bank in Moscow also
stated that its experts who will come to Moscow at the end of
November or the beginning of December will not offer any new loans
to Russia.
</P>
<P>
A source in the bank's office said the Russian administration
and the World Bank team will consider stepping up the work on the
budget-substituting loans for structural economic reforms approved
earlier by the bank's board.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank would like to see how Russia is implementing the
conditions for the release of the next payments out of these
loans.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, the two sides will also to discuss the
economic situation in the country in general.
</P>
<P>
This year the World Bank has given Russia the second and the
third tranches of a loan for the coal industry, 200 million U.S.
dollars each tranche; second tranche of the third loan on
structural economic reforms, 500 million U.S. dollars, and the
third tranche of the loan for the structural reform of the social
care system, 250 million U.S. dollars, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
