<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul
Ilah Al Khatib issued a statement here Monday to welcome the end
of the Iraqi-U.N. crisis over weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
With the end of the crisis, Jordan hoped that Iraq will soon
resume cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of eliminating weapons of mass destruction in Iraq,
Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
To resume cooperation with the UNSCOM and comply with
relevant U.N. resolutions are the sole way for Iraq to tackle the
current situation and get lifted the U.N. sanctions imposed on
Iraq eight years ago for its invasion of Kuwait, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced its decision to halt all cooperation with the
UNSCOM on October 31, triggering the standoff with the U.N.. The
United States then threatened to take military actions to force
Iraq into compliance.
</P>
<P>
Iraq last Saturday decided to unconditionally resume
cooperation with the UNSCOM. And the U.S. later temporarily
withdrew its military threats.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions cannot be lifted until UNSCOM verifies that
Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
