<HEADLINE> Tanzania Telecom Firm in Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned
Tanzania Telecommunication Company Limited (TTCL) has incurred a
loss of three billion Shillings (about 4.5 million U.S. Dollars)
caused by fraudulent practices over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
A senior TTCL official, who declined to be named, said in Dar
es Salaam that a lot of loopholes are existing in the
telecommunication industry in the country.
</P>
<P>
He named telephone tapping, illegal attended call offices,
operator calls and cutting lines as some of the areas where
fraudulent practices have taken place.
</P>
<P>
The official said the practices have also denied the
government a substantial amount of revenue.
</P>
<P>
To deal with defaulters, he said TTCL has set up a task force
composed of police officers and the company's investigators.
</P>
<P>
By June this year, he said, TTCL had carried out 20 operations
in cooperation with the police against defaulters in Dar es
Salaam and the central city of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
He said 21 suspects have been sent to court, 13 cases are
still under investigation and the police are still looking for
another 25 suspects.
</P>
<P>
But he said it is discouraging to note that some of the netted
culprits have been released in the court on bail, hence having
chances to continue with their malpractices.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, disciplinary measures have been taken
against 467 employees between 1993 and this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
