<HEADLINE> Israeli Spy Petitions Against Release of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Jonathan Pollard, a
convicted Israeli, on Monday petitioned Israel's High Court
against release of Palestinian prisoners in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Pollard, serving a life sentence in the
United States, asked the court to hold up the release of 250
Palestinian prisoners until his release by the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Under the land-for-peace deal signed by Israeli and Palestinian
leaders in Washington last month, Israel will release 750
Palestinian prisoners in three stages. The first one-third are
scheduled to be released later this week.
</P>
<P>
Pollard, an American Jew working as a U.S. naval intelligence
analyst, was arrested in 1985 and later convicted of spying for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The issue over his release almost foiled the recent
Israeli-Palestinian peace deal at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
Just hours before a signing ceremony at the White House, the
Israeli negotiation team said it would not attend the ceremony
unless U.S. President Bill Clinton secured Pollard's release.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was defused when Clinton promised to "review" the
case. But the ceremony was postponed by several hours.
</P>
<P>
Since Pollard's arrest, Clinton has rejected Israel's demands
on several occasions that he pardon Pollard, but Israel has vowed
time and again that it would take every measure to get Pollard
out of prison. 
</P>
