<HEADLINE> Lesotho Opposition Suspends Talks With Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's 12 opposition
parties have suspended talks with the government and Southern
African Development Community (SADC) mediators on the political
future of the country, South African television reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The opposition announcement came just hours before the
official launch of an interim political authority which is
supposed to pave the way for new elections in 18 months' time.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance said all participation on their part
will be halted until important security issues were discussed
with all stake holders.
</P>
<P>
The security issues included the release of rebel soldiers
charged with treason arising from the mutiny in the Lesotho
Defense Force on September 11.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties said the government of Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD) was harassing them. They accused the LCD of
expelling their supporters from work place and arresting their
members.
</P>
<P>
The opposition also accused the SADC mediators of siding with
the Lesotho government, saying they were doing nothing to stop
the harassment.
</P>
<P>
"We note that the undignified haste of the South African
authorities to lure us away from the palace refuge was a mere
ploy to unleash the hounds of dictatorship on us," said Mamello
Morrison, spokesperson for the opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
She was referring to South Africa's efforts to remove
opposition supporters from the royal palace.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has called for the withdrawal of SADC
peace-keeping troops from Lesotho, the release of their members
from detention and an end to further arrests. If the demands were
not met, they said, they would not go back to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the opposition alliance Vincent Malebo said: "The
LCD government and leader of the opposition alliance should
commit themselves to the spirit of normalization, by creating an
atmosphere of mutual trust, avoiding or desisting from utterances
and postures that seek to undermine the normalization and
reconciliation effort."
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Foreign Minister Tom Thabane said the opposition move
made no sense.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the opposition walkout, South African safety and
security minister Sydney Mufamadi said so far as he is concerned,
the process that would ultimately lead to fresh elections in 15
to 18 months' time is still on track.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi is the chief SADC mediator on the Lesotho political
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Following the military intervention of South African and
Botswana troops as SADC peace-keepers in Lesotho, the Lesotho
government and opposition parties agreed on the establishment of
an interim political structure in mid-October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
