<HEADLINE> Marriages Down, Divorces Up in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of marriages in Iran
is on decline while that of divorces is increasing, according to a
latest statistic report by the country's registration office.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 500,034 young couples got married in the
first half of the Iranian calendar year to end on March 20, 1999,
some 14,000 less than the number for the similar period last year.
</P>
<P>
"The decline is unprecedented in the last 20 years," said the
report.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the decline was more significant in Tehran
province, where only 75,186 couples tied the knot during the six
months, registering a drop of 13.11 percent compared to the figure
for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there were 40,806 divorces throughout the country
during the first half of the year, a rise of 1.58 percent from the
corresponding 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Due to the economic problems caused by oil price slump, many
Iranian parents cannot afford the houses, wedding expense and
dowries for young couples.
</P>
<P>
According to Iranian traditions, the parents of the bride must
prepare all necessary furniture for the new couple and the parents
of the bridegroom must prepare the house and the wedding expenses.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian authorities have taken some measures to encourage
young people to get married, such as allowing temperate marriage
in the country and holding mass weddings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0066 </DOCNO>
