<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Compensation for Brain Damaged Girl in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A 17-year-old British girl who
was severely brain damaged during routine surgery accepted a
record 3.9 million pounds (6.6 million U.S. dollars) damages from
a doctor on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Helen Edwards, from Suffolk, suffered the damage during an
operation to remove a birthmark on her forehead at the private
Hope Nursing Home in Cambridgeshire in 1986 when she was five
years old.
</P>
<P>
The High Court in London awarded her a record 3.9 million
pounds in damages on Monday -- the highest ever award in the UK
for an act of medical negligence.
</P>
<P>
Helen suffered complications from the anaesthetic and suffered
a cardiac arrest, which led to permanent and severe brain damage.
</P>
<P>
She was left blind and unable to crawl, feed or talk, although
she is now able to see and has recovered some movement.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Ogg, the consultant anaesthetist during the operation,
admitted liability in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, it has taken until now for the family to fight for the
amount of money they say is needed to provide for their daughter's
care regime.
</P>
<P>
The previous highest award was almost 3.3 million pounds (55
million U.S. dollars), which was made to Sam Mansell in October
this year.
</P>
<P>
He was severely disabled at birth, and has athetoid cerebral
palsy after being starved of oxygen during delivery by Caesarean
section in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
