<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Accuses S. Africa of Harboring Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC) Monday accused South Africa of harboring
rebels fighting to overthrow the DRC government led by President
Laurent Kabila, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"This is the place where the plot has started. South Africa is
really the home of the so-called rebels," Congolese Foreign
Minister Jean-Charles Okoto said in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"When you look around, there is not any other African country
where those rebels are receiving everything they need. They are
really welcome in South Africa."
</P>
<P>
Okoto is on a two-day visit to South Africa at the invitation
of his South African counterpart, Alfred Nzo.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Nzo in the morning, Okoto was in the afternoon
waiting for an opportunity to meet South African President Nelson
Mandela to convey to him a message from Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"I am still waiting," he said. "If I were the rebels, he
(Mandela) would have seen them already."
</P>
<P>
Okoto also expressed anger about South Africa's speedy
intervention in Lesotho while it neglected to condemn Uganda and
Rwanda for backing the rebels against the Kabila government.
</P>
<P>
Okoto said it was time South Africa assumed its responsibility
as the chairing country of the 14-member Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Asked if South Africa's alleged leniency toward the rebels was
deliberate, he said: "South Africa must have its own reasons.
This country is like a swimming pool where the rebels can swim
for as long as they want, and make their statements."
</P>
<P>
The Congolese community in South Africa had not been given a
chance to speak out in favor of Kabila, but the rebels, who
treated Kabila's Congo (K) like devils, were free to speak out
their minds.
</P>
<P>
Okoto intimated that Congo (K) had more information about the
support the rebels were receiving.
</P>
<P>
"We also have an intelligence service and have our people
among the rebels. We are informed about weapons and ammunition
they are getting, and even financial assistance they are getting
from foreign countries."
</P>
<P>
Okoto said he had raised his country's concerns with Nzo,
adding that he received a mixed response.
</P>
<P>
Nzo acknowledged that diplomatic ties between the two
countries had improved, but also insisted on the Congolese
government negotiating with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The Congolese are not little children. When the Rwandan
troops failed to take control of Kinshasa they hid behind the
so-called rebels," Okoto said.
</P>
<P>
Nzo earlier in the day said uncertainty about the role the
rebels would play in peace efforts was a serious stumbling block
in attaining a cease-fire in Congo.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the conflict in Congo was not a military
problem but a political one that should be solved by the people
of Congo themselves.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a call by Congo for an African peace-keeping
force to be deployed along its borders, Nzo said such a force
should involve the United Nations and was something for the
future.
</P>
<P>
Conditions for a peace-keeping force first had to be created.
Once that happened, countries would be approached to take part in
such a force.
</P>
<P>
"If South Africa is approached, it will play a role. The
specific role will be decided by our government," Nzo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
