<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder: Russia Must Answer IMF to Get New Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder warned Tuesday that Russia can get further
financial aid only when its "economic program is made more
concrete", according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Speaker of the Russian State Duma (the lower
house), Gennady Seleznyov, Schroeder said the economic situation
in Russia was "grave", but the Russian government's program of
priority measures was "a good foundation, on which work with the
international financial organizations can be continued".
</P>
<P>
On the aid of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), he said
that "motivation of the second tranche of its credit is on the
order of the day, and the Russian government and parliament must
bear particular responsibility in this case".
</P>
<P>
"They must find answers to the IMF questions, and if they
succeed in doing so, we shall be ready to help Russia by words and
deeds," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov, on his part, expressed confidence that
Russian-German ties in all the areas would be continued,
especially those between the two nations' parliaments.
</P>
<P>
First Vice-Speaker of the Russian Duma, Vladimir Ryzhkov, who
also attended the meeting, said that Germany still regarded
relations with Russia as one of its main priorities on the
international arena.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder arrived in Moscow for two-day official visit on
Monday. He has met with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, two
speakers of the Russian Parliament, Seleznyov and Yegor Stroyev,
Russian Communist Party Leader Gennady Zyuganov and other Russian
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder is expected to return home on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
