<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Schroeder Agree on Further Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and visiting German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder agreed
Tuesday to maintain the rapid development of ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders shared the view that Russian-German relations
had no insurmountable hurdles, Deputy Head of the Russian
Presidential Administration Sergei Prikhodko said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told the German Chancellor that "the most important
thing is that relations between Germany and Russia are, and will
be, just the same as they were in recent years".
</P>
<P>
Both Yeltsin and Schroeder confirmed the value of the
large-scale consultations on all matters concerning bilateral
cooperation involving key ministries, Prikhodko said.
</P>
<P>
However, Germany would not give new loans to Russia, Schroeder
said in a televised interview in Moscow Monday. Germany's credit
capacity was very limited, and Germany would not be able to help
Russia on a bilateral basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor praised Russian government's anti-crisis
program, calling it a good foundation for further assistance from
international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Yeltsin informed Schroeder about the Russian
government's recent efforts to stabilize the country's social and
economic situation, Prikhodko added.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder expressed his thanks to Yeltsin for Russia's
constructive role in settling the crises in Kosovo and Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
