<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Leaves Moscow for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 17 (Xinhua) -- German Federal Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder wound up his two-day official visit to Russia
and flew to Bonn on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During the visit Schroeder met with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, two speakers of the Russian Parliament, Gennady Seleznyov
and Yegor Stroyev, Russian Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov
and other high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of Russia and German agreed that relations between
the two countries should be maintained at the same level as before
and further developed.
</P>
<P>
"The most important result of the visit is in the confirmation
of the course for the development of intensive relations between
the two countries," head of the foreign-policy department of the
chancellor Michael Steiner said at a press conference Tuesday
after the meeting between Yeltsin and Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said in a televised interview on Monday evening that
Germany is not going to extend new loans to Russia. Germany's
crediting capacity has become very limited, Germany would not be
able to help Russia on a bilateral basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor noted that Russia can get further
financial aid only when the government's economic program is made
more concrete.
</P>
<P>
He meanwhile praised the economic program, saying that the
program of priority measures is "a good foundation, on which work
with the international financial organizations can be continued."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the IMF aid, Schroeder said that the Russian
government and the parliament must find answers to the IMF
questions, and if they succeed in doing it, Germany will be ready
to help Russia by words and deeds. 
</P>
