<HEADLINE> S. Africa Neutral In Congo (K) Conflict: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Tuesday
denied allegations by the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) that
it was harboring rebels trying to overthrow the DRC government
led by President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said in a statement that his
country remained neutral in its quest to find a solution to the
DRC crisis.
</P>
<P>
DRC Foreign Minister Jean-Charles Okoto Lolakombe, who had
talks Monday with Nzo over the DRC conflict in Pretoria, capital
of South Africa, told reporters that DRC rebels were welcomed and
given support in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"This is the place where the plot has started. South Africa
is really the home of the so-called rebels," Lolakombe said.
</P>
<P>
Denying the accusation, Nzo said his country was a
constitutional democracy which attracted many people of differing
political persuasions.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the rebels did not mean the South African
government favored them or provided them with logistical or moral
support, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leaders who met President Nelson Mandela in Pretoria
recently were not resident here, but only on a brief visit after
the October 27 Lusaka meeting on the DRC conflict, said the
foreign minister. 
</P>
