<HEADLINE> Nasser's Son Denounces Call For Downfall of Saddam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Khalid Nasser, son of the late
Egyptian President Jamal Abudul Nasir, on Tuesday criticized
U.S. President Bill Clinton for calling for the downfall of Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Iraqi News Agency, Khalid, chairman of
Nasserist Party, said any calls to interfere in Iraq's internal
affairs will be rejected as they violate the U.N. Charter as well
as the international law.
</P>
<P>
Khalid is currently in Baghdad to attend a conference on
medicine.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said on Sunday the U.S. government will support the
efforts of Iraqi opposition to topple Saddam when he announced
Iraq had narrowly averted a military strike by backing down from
its defiance of U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Saturday resumed unconditional cooperation with the
U.N. Speical Commission (UNSCOM) for disarming Iraq and the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). It halted all its
dealings with UNSCOM on October 31.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak on Tuesday met
with Khalid and briefed him on the health situation in Iraq.
</P>
