<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   British Court Sets Deadline in Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 17 (Xinhua) - A British court ruled on Tuesday
that the government must decide by December 2 whether to allow a
court to hold a hearing into Spain's appeal for the extradition of
former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
But Magistrate Graham Parkinson said he would be prepared to
consider legal applications for the December deadline to be
extended if necessary.
</P>
<P>
A hearing is scheduled to be held in England's High Court on
Wednesday on the conditions of Pinochet's bail, which would allow
him to appear in court.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's lawyer, Alun Jones, said on Tuesday the 82-year-old
general was "fit to be discharged from hospital".
</P>
<P>
Pinochet has been under guard since October 16 in a London
hospital where he was treated as a patient with a diplomatic
passport.
</P>
<P>
A Spanish court had requested his extradition from the United
Kingdom on charges of murder, torture and kidnapping during his
17-year rule in Chile which ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The British House of Lords has yet to rule on whether Pinochet
is immune from prosecution. If it decides that Pinochet enjoys
diplomatic immunity, the extradition process would be halted and
the former general would be free to leave Britain immediately and
fly home to Chile.  
</P>
</TEXT>
