<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Political Contact with Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian
Consulate-General in Peshawar denied on Tuesday holding of any
political dialogue with the Afghan Taliban militia for re-opening
of its diplomatic mission in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Iranian Consulate-General
clarified that only a group of Iranian technicians had proceeded
to Afghanistan to inspect the properties of the Iranian consulates
in Afghanistan, which are now under the control of the Taliban
militia.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan Islamic Press, a Peshawar-based private news
agency, reported Monday that a high level Iranian government
delegation has visited the Taliban headquarters of Kandahar and
held talks with the Taliban leaders to prepare ground for possible
meeting between Taliban leader Mullah Omar and Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharazi.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian Consulate-General denied the report and
said in its press release that Iran did not hold any kind of
political dialogue with the Taliban for re-opening of its
diplomatic mission.
</P>
<P>
The press release indicated that re-opening of its diplomatic
mission could only be possible after the punishment of the killers
of Iranian diplomats in the northern Afghan town of Mazar-e-S
Harif, an apology by the Taliban over this incident, release of
the remaining Iranian prisoners and restoration of peace and
security in that country.  
