<HEADLINE> China Making Progress In Dealing With Millenium Bug Problem (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China's banking, finance, tax,
telecommunications, civil aviation, and power sectors have made
progress in dealing with the millenium bug problem by advancing
computer systems 410 days before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Information Industry Minister Wu Jichuan said today that these
sectors have entered the final phase of computer tests and expect
to solve all problems that will be discovered by the end of
September, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Richard Scurfield, with the World Bank's China Program, says
that the World Bank is positive about China's handling of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Information Industry, Ministry of Finance, and
The World Bank held a seminar here November 17-18, where Zhang Qi,
chairperson of the MII's Y2K Committee, said that China has been
working on the Y2K problem since 1996. So far, the five major
commercial banks have completed inventories of their computer
systems and improved 70 percent of their software. They are
cooperating closely with local and foreign suppliers and the
People's Bank of China, the central bank, is drafting emergency
plans to move smoothly into the new millenium.
</P>
<P>
The China Securities Regulatory Commission started testing the
country's securities computing network in September and will run
another test November 28.
</P>
<P>
The State Tax Administration will complete its computer
inventory by the end of this year and will focus on upgrading its
software.
</P>
<P>
China Telecoms is on schedule in upgrading its
telecommunications network and says it will solve the Y2K problem
and maintain normal operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
