<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Faces Aging Population Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Hungary will experience an
average drop of 40,000 to 45,000 people in its population from
now to 2050, making the aging problem more and more outstanding.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released by the Nepszabasag
newspaper on Tuesday, Hungary in 1997 had 10.14 million people.
Experts predicted the number would fall to eight million by 2015
and those above 50 years would account for 50 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed that Hungary's population decline is
accelerating. It is predicted that by 2015, the number of babies
born every year will decrease to 90,000 from 148,000 in 1980. By
2050, the number will further drop to 70,000.
</P>
<P>
Due to the fall in both birth and death rates, old people are
making up a larger proportion of the population. The aging
population, which will result in challenges over retirement
policy, pensions and social insurance, will become the major
social problem for the Hungarian government at the end of this
century and the beginning of the next.
</P>
<P>
The shrinking population started in 1981. From 1980 to 1997,
the total number of Hungarian residents dropped by 563,000. Last
year, the natural growth rate hit a new low record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
