<HEADLINE> Y2K Problem (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Administration of China has discovered that
70 percent of its computer systems have Y2K problems and has
classified its branches according to degree of severity and has
helped them find solutions. On July 4, it successfully upgraded
its booking system and modified software. The Boeing Company
confirmed shortly afterward that CAAC's Boeing fleet has no
problems.
</P>
<P>
The China Petrochemical Group has set up four panels to address
the problem and the State Metallurgy Administration and the
Ministry of Communications have started looking into the problem.
</P>
<P>
China has more than ten million computers and the number is
growing at a rate of 50 percent every year.
</P>
<P>
Wu says, since China depends on computers far less than
developed countries do, the amount of work that needs to be done
is much less, but the job is still difficult because China gets
its equipment from a wide range of suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K question is more one of management than of technology,
he says, and believes that if institutions and enterprises pay
enough attention to the problem and use plenty of resources and
technology, China will not have the serious problems that some
foreigners expect at the turn of the century. 
</P>
