<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Amhara state, a major
cereals and pulse producer in Ethiopia, expected to harvest over
4.2 million tons of crop this year, a 10 percent increase over
that of last year.
</P>
<P>
The harvest is attributed to good rainfall this year and
the extension program in the country as whole, the local
authorities announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Belay Demissie, head of the state's agricultural bureau, told
the Ethiopian News Agency that the extension package has covered
920,442 demonstrated sites encompassing activities such as crop
development, animal husbandry, and conservation of national
resources.
</P>
<P>
Belay said about 62,000 hectares of land has been developed
through irrigation and more than 83,900 tons of selected seeds
and fertilizers have been distributed among farmers.
</P>
<P>
An earlier announcement from the Ethiopian Ministry of
Agriculture also predicted a good harvest in the Horn of Africa
country this year as a result of good weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Ethiopia yielded 8.786 million tons of crops, 25
percent below the harvest in 1996. 
