<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Suffering From Chronic Oversupply of Cement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chronic oversupply, dwindling
exports and mounting debt problems are crippling Vietnam's cement
industry, fueling calls for greater government intervention to
save the sector, Vietnam Investment Review reported in its latest
issue.
</P>
<P>
According to the English-language weekly, Vietnam's cement
production capacity is expected to reach 16.8 million tons by the
end of this year, but with yearly domestic consumption of only 9.5
million tons and export levels almost nil, the market is suffering
from chronic oversupply.
</P>
<P>
"Cement supply has dramatically outweighed domestic demand this
year and export markets are steadily shrinking, leaving local
producers in fear of insolvency", said a senior official from
Vietnam Cement Corporation last week.
</P>
<P>
The weekly said current domestic consumption targets of 12
million tons next year and 15 million tons by 2000 are fanciful.
</P>
<P>
Local produced cement now sells for between 56 and 62 U.S.
dollars per ton, while Thai and Chinese equivalents sell for 39
and 35 U.S. dollars respectively, the review said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's cement industry is almost completely dependent on
foreign loan capital, with about 90 percent of investment capital
in cement projects came from international loans, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Recent dong (Vietnamese currency) devaluation have added higher
loan service payments to production costs, increasing prices by 2
to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Debt servicing is definitely contributing to rising production
costs. interest on loans amount to 30 percent of our costs", said
one cement production executive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
