<HEADLINE> China Issuing 2 Billion Yuan Worth Of Three Gorges Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China plans to issue another 2
billion yuan worth of Three Gorges construction bonds in January
1999, according to Li Yong'an, the deputy-general manager of the
China Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
The first 1 billion yuan worth of Three Gorges bonds were sold
in 1996 and the company is expected to sell 10 to 12 billion yuan
worth of enterprise bonds during the second phase of the Three
Gorges Project, Li says.
</P>
<P>
Other means like loans and shares will be used to raise funds
for the second phase of the project, he says. The second phase
will cost 80 billion yuan and a total of 25 billion yuan is
expected to be raised on the market. The rest will come from the
government.
</P>
<P>
Half of next year's bonds will have a three-year term and half,
an eight-year term. They have a very low risk credit assessment.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen major domestic securities firms are competing to
underwrite the bonds.  
