<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Southern China To More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of
China's Guangdong Province will open more to overseas investment
and will use it more efficiently, Vice-mayor Wu Liang said today.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Guangzhou used 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars worth of overseas investment in the January-October
period of this year, 7 percent more than for the same period in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The city has used 14.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of overseas
investment in the past two decades, which contributed much to the
14.3 percent growth in Guangzhou's annual GDP.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the industrial output of overseas-backed enterprises
accounted for 44.6 percent of the city's total and exports of
overseas-backed enterprises accounted for 60.7 percent of its
total.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment is being encouraged for the service
industry, high-tech industry, and state-owned large and
medium-sized enterprises, Wu says.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors will be allowed to set up joint ventures in
tourism and service sectors, such as travel agencies handling
international business, holiday resorts and consultation
firms.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the city also plans to open electronic
information networks which could be paid both in Guangzhou and
neighboring Hong Kong, adding that more foreign banks and
insurance companies are encouraged to open branches or offices in
the city.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in 1999, Guangzhou will work out a list of key
projects for overseas investment and open offices in Hong Kong and
San Francisco to attract investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
