<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin: Supervision Needed to Curb Capital Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua)-- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin called on Tuesday for greater controls on speculative
activities with large sums of international floating capital which
had severely damaged the economies of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to supervise and control the excessive
speculation of the international floating capital," Jiang said
while meeting Malaysian Prime Minister Dr. Mahathir Mohamad here
in the Malaysian capital.
</P>
<P>
"Eventually, it will be disastrous for the developed countries
if such things go on rampantly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the economic development of East Asia over the past
30 years was a known fact. The financial crisis prompted people to
re-examine the problems in the process of economic development of
their countries, so they could undertake necessary reforms.
</P>
<P>
"From this point of view, the crisis is also a good thing to
some extent," Jiang said, adding the economic globalization had
not only brought about severe challenges for developing countries,
but opportunities as well.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Southeast Asian countries, including Malaysia,
will eventually conquer the crisis and revitalize their economies
and maintain a healthy development," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President said he was happy to see that Malaysia
had adopted policies that complied with its national realities,
and its national economy was turning for the better.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir gave Jiang a briefing on the economic situation in
Malaysia and the measures and policies it had taken to overcome
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The crisis which started in East Asia had spread throughout the
world, and become an world-wide problem. The destructive quality
of the capital speculation was obvious, said Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
Expressing appreciation of China maintaining the value of its
currency, Mahathir stressed that supervision and management of the
speculative activities of the international floating capital
should be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he was optimistic about the future development of
the economy of Malaysia as it was now turning for the better.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also expressed satisfaction over the smooth
development of the bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
