<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Merge Land Fund Into Exchange Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government announced Tuesday that
the assets of the Land Fund will be merged into the Exchange Fund.
</P>
<P>
The reference date for the merger is October 31, 1998, when the
assets of the Land Fund amounted to 211.4 billion HK dollars (27
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the Government's effort to streamline the
investment management of its accumulated fiscal reserves. The
fiscal reserves already placed with the Exchange Fund totaled
203.1 billion HK dollars (26 billion U.S. dollars) as on October
31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said Tuesday: "This exercise
will enable greater administrative efficiency and economies of
scale in the management of our accumulated fiscal reserves,
including the Land Fund, as I promised to achieve in my 1998-99
Budget Speech."
</P>
<P>
The Land Fund will remain a separate government fund after the
merger, but will enjoy the same rate of return as that of the
Exchange Fund, as in the case of the fiscal reserves, in
accordance with the arrangements laid down in the 1998-99
Financial Budget, the government sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong equity portfolio previously held in the Land Fund
will be passed over to the Exchange Fund Investment Limited (EFIL)
for management in the same manner as the those acquired by the
Exchange Fund in the market operation in August.
</P>
<P>
All Hong Kong equity holdings of the HKSAR will therefore be
consolidated for management by EFIL.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's foreign currency assets, held either in the
Exchange Fund or the Land Fund, reached 88.4 billion U.S. dollars
as at the end of September, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
