<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livent Set to Seek Bankruptcy Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The largest live theater
producer in North America, Livent Incorporation, is expected to
file for bankruptcy protection in Canada and United States, the
Canadian National Post newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto-based company has debts of 230 million Canadian
dollars (149.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources close to the company as saying it
is preparing to file court documents in New York and a similar
action in Canada under the Companies Creditors' Arrangement Act.
</P>
<P>
Although Livent's board of directors has yet to make a final
decision, lawyers have been instructed to prepare court materials
to seek relief from creditors in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Livent lost 44 million Canadian dollars in 1997 and has written
off more than 60 million Canadian dollars in costs that can't be
recouped since last December.
</P>
<P>
The company is the producer of such mega-shows as "Phantom of
the Opera", "Ragtime" and "Show Boat".
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy protection will allow Livent to buy some much-needed
time to restructure its financial house.
</P>
<P>
The company is not insolvent, but by seeking bankruptcy
protection it buys time to reorganize without the pressure of
paying its creditors until a plan is approved by the company's
debtors and the court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
