<HEADLINE> China Maintaining Housing Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China expects to build more
than 300 million sq.m. of housing in urban areas, and more than
650 million sq.m. in the countryside, according to Vice-Minister
of Construction Song Chunhua.
</P>
<P>
Song told the national housing construction conference here
today that China's housing industry has helped develop the
national economic development and consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
The country has reform measures for the housing system this
year and has spent 170 billion yuan building 210 million sq.m. of
affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
Song says that the 1.6 billion sq.m. of urban and rural housing
built over the past five years has solved the housing problem for
over six million households, and the average per-capita living
space has grown to 8.8 sq m, in urban areas and to 22.6 sq.m. in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
To improve housing conditions, China has an "affordable housing
project" in more than 200 cities and housing cooperatives have
added more fund-raising channels and have benefited low- to
medium-income households.
</P>
<P>
Construction departments have made an effort to improve water
supplies, sewage, heating, roads, bridges, highways, trees, and
environmental protection systems to improve the standard of living.
</P>
<P>
Urban housing construction is expected to account for about 4
percent of the country's GDP in the coming years, Song says, and
plans for 2000 call for one billion sq.m. of housing, and some 70
percent of the households able to afford well-equipped houses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
