<HEADLINE> S. Korean Soccer Officials Charged With Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Local prosecutors here have
charged 29 coaches, officials and parents Tuesday with taking or
giving bribes to arrange for high school soccer players to enter
colleges or national junior teams.
</P>
<P>
Twelve high school and college soccer coaches and one referee
were indicted Monday on charges of receiving bribes of up to
32,000 U.S. dollars each from parents of high school athletes
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors also charged 16 parents with paying bribes.
</P>
<P>
They said the referee fixed matches so that certain players
would score more and accused the coaches of influence-peddling in
selecting players for college soccer teams and the national
junior team.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said all 16 soccer players under question have
entered colleges or have been selected as national junior soccer
players, but did not reveal their names.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty, those charged face up to five years in
prison. 
</P>
