<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Discusses Pension, Asset Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chief representatives of both
sides of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG) discussed
issues concerning the pension for retired Macao civil servants
and the transfer of assets.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the two parties discussed the problem of
so-called official status of Portuguese in the future, which was
put forward by the Portuguese side.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang, chief representative of the Chinese side, said
after a four-hour meeting with his counterpart Santana Carlos that
the two sides should focus on the affairs directly related to
Macao's power transfer and smooth handover as the transition
period becomes rather short.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides should take the pension problem concerning retired
civil servants and the problem of asset transfer as problems which
are of close connection and great significance with the power
transfer and smooth handover," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Basic Law stipulates that government of the future
Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) will pay pensions to
civil servants retired after the SAR is established. But the
Portuguese side claims that the SAR government should also
pay the pensions to those retired before the SAR is set up.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese representative said that the pension problem should
be settled in accordance with the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration and the Macao Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the transfer of assets, Han Zhaokang expressed
his hope that the Portuguese side should work out a list of
Macao's assets as soon as possible and give it to the Chinese
side, so that the two parties can hold further discussions on the
transfer of Macao's assets.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the use of Portuguese in the future Macao SAR,
Han said that the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and the Macao
Basic Law stipulate that Portuguese will be an official language
in the SAR. The status of Portuguese does not pose a problem
either at present or in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
