<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Weapons Inspectors Return to Iraq by Huang Xingwei, Liu Jiawen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of 86 U.N. weapons
inspectors returned to Iraq aboard a chartered plane Tuesday, only
to find themselves being greeted by peace activists calling for
ending sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
As the latest Iraq-U.N. standoff over arms inspections abated,
the U.N. chartered plane carrying the inspectors landed at the
Habbaniya airport, 80 kilometers west of Baghdad, around noon
local time.
</P>
<P>
When the inspectors arrived at the Baghdad Monitoring and
Verification Center at 1:40 p.m. (1040 GMT), six Americans of the
Voices in the Wilderness, a U.S. and British anti-sanctions
campaign, were protesting outside the compound.
</P>
<P>
Holding banners of "Ending sanctions - not lives" and
"Sanctions are starving to death 6,000 Iraqi infants every month,"
they sang peaceful songs when the convoy filed in.
</P>
<P>
Mira Tenaa, a member of the non-governmental organization,
told Xinhua that they rushed to Baghdad from Chicago following
the United States' threat of a military strike to force Iraqi
compliance over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
She said her group members were warned by U.S. government that
they would face penalties back home for travelling to Iraq, a
violation of U.S. laws, of up to 12 years in prison and over 1
million U.S. dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. policy is silent yet deadly warfare. The Iraqi
people, the children in particular, are innocent, but they became
victims of the sanctions," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Although a military attack was averted, the sanctions are
still killing the Iraqi people silently," said Ken Ricardi, a
father of four.
</P>
<P>
One arms inspector told Xinhua on condition of anonymity that
they would hold discussions later Tuesday on how to conduct
inspections beginning from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler last Wednesday
ordered the withdrawal of most of his staff in Baghdad, about 100
in total, on "strong recommendation" from U.S. government, which
said a military strike against Iraq was imminent.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference Monday in
New York that the U.N. Special Commission in charge of disarming
Iraq (UNSCOM) "is expected to resume its duty on Wednesday."
</P>
<P>
Eckhard also said that another six UNSCOM staff will return to
Baghdad on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a group of 30 U.N. humanitarian workers returned to
Baghdad on a U.N. flight to resume relief tasks in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 more U.N. humanitarian staff also arrived here Tuesday
from Jordanian capital of Amman.
</P>
<P>
Iraq averted possible U.S. and British air strikes at the last
minute by agreeing on Saturday to allow the resumption of
U.N. arms inspection unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, Iraq decided to ban UNSCOM and the International
Atomic Energy Agency from conducting field inspections of new
sites, but allowed monitoring activities to continue.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership took a step further on October 31 by
halting all cooperation with UNSCOM until the U.N. Security
Council moves toward the lifting of economic sanctions imposed
after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM
verify that Iraq has come clean of all weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
