<HEADLINE> Philippines Trade Deficit Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
shrank by 88.6 percent to 962 million U.S. dollars for the first
three quarters of 1998 from 8.419 billion dollars a year ago while
total trade dropped slightly, the National Statistics Office said.
</P>
<P>
For September 1998, balance of trade surged by 153.6 percent to
a surplus value of 332 million dollars from a deficit level of 619
million dollars last year, the office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Total trade slipped by 1.1 percent to 44.653 billion dollars
from 45.145 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the nine months, the country's imports totaled about 22.81
billion dollars, the office said.
</P>
<P>
During this period, The United States emerged as the biggest
source of imports with a 22.34-percent share. It was followed by
Japan with a share of 20.29 percent and South Korea 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Electronics and components topped the imports with a
21.7-percent share for September alone, rising by 6.3 percent to
531.76 million dollars over 500.38 million dollars recorded a
year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
