<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Ease of Iraqi Crisis: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government welcomes
Iraq's decision to unconditionally resume cooperation with the UN
Special Commission and the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA), Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tang said at a regular news briefing that China has always
stuck to a peaceful solution of the weapons inspection crisis,
maintained close contacts with other permenant members of the UN
Security Council and relevant nations, and tried to persuade all
parties concerned to achieve a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin sent a special letter to U.S. President
Bill Clinton to exchange views on the situation when the crisis
deteriorated, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Jiang urged the Iraqi government to resume
cooperation with the UN as soon as possible and implement relevant
resolutions of the Security Council. Jiang also stressed China's
stand of opposing the use of force in the resolvement of
international disputes.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China's Vice-Premier Qian Qichen sent a letter to
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minsiter Tareq Aziz, urging the Iraqi side to
rapidly resume cooperation with the UN to avoid a further
deterioration of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China, together with other permanent
members of the UN Security Council and relevant parties, has
played a constructive role in promoting the mediation of the UN
secretary-general, who wrote to Iraqi leaders.
</P>
<P>
Immediately afater that, China's Minister of Foreign Affairs
Tang Jiaxuan also sent a letter to the Iraqi foreign minister on
November 14, urging Iraqi leaders to make a good judgement of
the situation and immediately resume cooperation with the special
commission.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the Iraqi side to keep its promise to earnestly
implement relevant resolutions of the UN Security Council," said
Tang. "We also call on all relevant parties to continue their
political and diplomatic efforts so as to resolve the disputes and
problems in the weapons inspection." 
</P>
