<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunken Ship Discovered In World's Longest Canal (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A wooden ship that has been
embedded on the floor of China's Great canal for a century was
discovered recently by Chinese archaeologists, covered in silt at
the northern end of the Canal in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The wood of the 14.7-meter-long, six-meter-wide ship is still
rather hard even though it has rotted some in the past 100 years,
according to Wang Wuyu, deputy director of the Beijing Relics
Research Institute, and that it is a rare find since it is intact.
</P>
<P>
Wang and his colleagues have discovered shards of Yuan
(1271-1368), Ming (1368-1644), and Qing (1644-1911) dynasty
pottery and copper coins from the Ming and Qing near the ship and
say they believe these scattered relics have some connection with
the ship. They are trying to fix the exact age of the ship.
</P>
<P>
Things are not going very smoothly because of the thick silt
and groundwater, Wang says, but they expect to solve the mystery
of the ship in a week or so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ship In World's Longest Canal (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Workers discovered the ship during dredging work for a road
that will intersect the almost dry canal in the Tongzhou District
in the eastern part of the city.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, ships carrying tribute to
the emperors did sink from time to time during different
dynasties, but were often not salvaged.
</P>
<P>
The 1,747-kilometer canal ran from Beijing to the city of
Hangzhou in Zhejiang Province. Digging started under orders from
an emperor of the Sui Dynasty (581-618). It runs almost parallel
to China's eastern coastline, and once was 2,700 kilometers long.
</P>
<P>
It was an important waterway for transporting rice from south
China to north China, but many parts of it were abandoned when the
part in today's Shandong Province silted up 170 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Many people are said to have tried to salvage sunken ships
before but none succeeded. There were attempts in the 1960s and
1970s by cultural relics and water conservation bureaus.
</P>
<P>
Wang says he believes they'll succeed if water conservation and
cultural relics departments cooperate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
