<HEADLINE> Arafat Retracts Threats over Disputes with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 17 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to cool a war
of words with Israel, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat pledged on
Tuesday that he would only use peaceful means to resolve disputes,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Israeli prime minister reportedly said Benjamin
Netanyahu has accepted what he called Arafat's retraction of
threats to declare a Palestinian state in May 4 next year and
revive armed struggle for Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is a strategic choice for the Palestinian people" and
therefore any problems concerning final-status issues will be
resolved through "amicable and peaceful" negotiations rather than
any other ways, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks at a joint news conference with
visiting German President Roman Herzog in the West Bank town of
Jericho.
</P>
<P>
This came a day after Netanyahu announced to hold up the
handover of the next chunk of the West Bank to the Palestinians
because of Arafat's threat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed his vow on the weekend to declare a Palestinian
state when the Oslo peace deal expires next year and warned of
another armed uprising to defend Jerusalem, which the Palestinians
want as capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu demanded a public retraction of the statements
before he moved on to carry out the first stage of the already
delayed further Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank, as called
for by their October 23 Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
With his senior aides claiming the statements were
"misunderstood," Arafat went on Israeli television Monday night to
explain that the Palestinians are committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's remarks Tuesday laid emphasis on that the Palestinians
would be seeking peaceful solutions to any problems, including the
status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli parliament, which resumed debate Tuesday over the
land-for-security deal signed last month, is expected to approve
its later in the day by a significant majority due to the support
of the left-wing lawmakers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
