<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
Tuesday closed marginally higher, but off its session highs, as
the debut of Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus captured most interest and
investors waited for U.S. news on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Optus, which has 16-percent weighting in the All Ordinaries
Index, debuted at 2.61 Australian dollars, peaked at 2.74 and
closed at 2.65 on a record turnover of 316.9 million.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed 2.1 points, or 0.08 percent,
higher at 2,676.6, and traded between 2,696.7 and 2,668.1.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the U.S. Federal Reserve's Federal Open Markets
Committee meeting Tuesday night meant that investors exercised
caution ahead of a possible rate cut.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we've had a great amount of information from the
U.S. on what the Fed's going to do," Grant Williams of Reynolds &AMP;
Co. said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said there were some concerns among investors at
the recent sharp gains on Wall Street, but they were "a little bit
more relaxed" than two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Lower base metal prices at the London Metal Exchange and a drop
in the December crude oil contract in New York led the All
Resources Index down 6.9 points to 1,049.4.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank, which closed up 36.5 cents, or 1.6
percent, at 23.15 Australian dollars, led the All Industrials
Index 11.2 points higher to 4,695, but off a high of 4728.6.
</P>
<P>
A fall in the price of gold bullion pushed the gold index 20.1
points or 1.71 percent lower to 1,162.1.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed 1.15 U.S. dollars lower at 293.7 dollars an
ounce.
</P>
<P>
BHP fell 5 cents and WMC dropped 18, but Rio Tinto, which has
lost ground in recent sessions, gained 15.6 cents.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained 8 cents and Westpac
Banking Corp. climbed 2.1, but ANZ Banking Group dropped 23 cents,
or 2.26 percent.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 615.97 million shares valued at 1.65
billion Australian dollars (1.04 billion U.S. dollars), with 558
falls and 458 rises while 416 stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
