<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Agrees to Be PEG Founder Patron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad has agreed to become the founder patron of the
Partnership for Equitable Growth (PEG) proposed by the APEC
Business Advisory Council (ABAC), which is expected to start
operation by early 1999.
</P>
<P>
PEG, targeted to be set up by year-end with its incorporation
completed by January 31, 1999, will act as a catalyst for private
sector involvement in Economic and Technical Cooperation (ECOTECH)
initiatives such as the APEC IT (information technology) Education
Initiative, the Clean Technology in China and the Kuala Lumpur
Plan for APEC Scholars, an ABAC official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
ECOTECH is one of the two pillars of APEC. The other one is
Trade and Investment Liberalization and Facilitation.
</P>
<P>
Based in Kuala Lumpur, PEG will operate as a non-profit
distributing organization with its own legal and independent
personnel, and aims at reducing economic disparities among APEC
economies and deepening the spirit of community in the
Asia-Pacific region, PEG Task Force Chair Francis Yeoh said.
</P>
<P>
The official said PEG's operating budget for the first three
years is estimated at three million U.S. dollars and the Malaysian
government will provide the seed money of one-third of the initial
budget.
</P>
<P>
He said PEG members will consist of individual corporations or
consortium of corporations from the 21 APEC member economies, with
at least three companies from each economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Malaysia, Indonesia, Brunei, Hong
Kong of China and Chinese Taipei have already confirmed their
membership in PEG.
</P>
<P>
ABAC is in a dialogue Tuesday with APEC leaders who are here
for their two-day 6th informal meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
