<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar slid
backward Tuesday, suffering a sell-off of almost half a U.S. cent
as the support that pushed it through 64 U.S. cents overnight
failed.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trade, the local unit was buying 63.33 U.S.
cents from 63.79 late Monday.
</P>
<P>
In offshore trade overnight it managed to achieve 64.05 U.S.
cents as the Japanese yen also gained ground, pushing the U.S.
dollar through 120 yen.
</P>
<P>
Yet both currencies found the going tougher, particularly after
an announcement that international rating agency Moody's Investors
Service had downgraded Japan's sovereign debt.
</P>
<P>
"Earlier in the day we drifted off from the highs, really it
was just disappointment that the Aussie couldn't go on with it
through 64 U.S. cents," Colonial State Bank treasury manager
Andrew Willett said.
</P>
<P>
Despite its earlier strength the Japanese yen weakened Tuesday
afternoon following Moody's announcement.
</P>
<P>
By the close of trade in Sydney, the U.S. dollar had recovered
a little ground but was still lower at 121.23 Japanese yen from
122.49 here previously.
</P>
<P>
The rating agency blamed the downgrade on Japan's weak
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Willett said this provided a catalyst for a further fall in the
Australian dollar, which dipped to a low of 63.1 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The key event for both foreign exchange and debt markets
Tuesday night is a meeting of the U.S. Federal Reserve's Open
Markets Committee.
</P>
<P>
U.S. analysts seem evenly split over the likelihood of a cut in
interest rates following the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile on the foreign exchange cross-rates the Australian
dollar was buying 76.83 Japanese yen from 78.12 and 1.0559 German
marks from 1.0699. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
