<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, New Zealand Value Emerging Markets Experience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China's Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and New Zealand agreed on Tuesday
that the experience of the emerging markets is most valuable
because they have been at the receiving end of the financial chaos.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa made the remarks while
meeting with New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley here.
</P>
<P>
They exchanged views on how to push forward G-7 and G-22
initiatives on the international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
Both Tung and Shipley are here to attend the 6th APEC informal
leaders meeting on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Tung said APEC leaders should focus on
four key issues -- the financial chaos, economic and technical
cooperation, electronic commerce and the strengthening of the
multilateral trading system, according to a press release by the
Hong Kong delegation.
</P>
<P>
"There will be an important dialogue on the financial crisis
and I would particularly like to share with other leaders Hong
Kong's experience in dealing with the financial turmoil," Tung was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tung said he would like to see APEC firmly support commitments
by G-7 and G-22 to address weaknesses in the international
financial architecture, especially in regards to enhancing the
transparency and accountability of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
APEC leaders held a dialogue Tuesday with APEC Business
Advisory Council (ABAC) on the financial chaos which covered
several topics, including the strengthening of financial and legal
systems, recapitalizing banks affected by bad debts and ways to
guard against contagion during regional economic turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
