<HEADLINE> WFP Provides Food Assistance to Refugees in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
agreed Tuesday to provide some 6.26 million U.S. dollars for the
procurement of food for the Bhutanese refugees staying in Nepal,
Nepal's official RSS news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Under a letter of understanding signed here between the WFP and
the Nepali government, the WFP assistance for the year 1999 will
provide basic food rations to 94,500 registered Bhutanese refugees
living in seven U.N.-run camps in Jhapa and Morang districts,
eastern Nepal, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Supplementary food rations will be provided to refugee
children, pregnant women, nursing mothers, patients and old
people, it added.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the provision of food items, the WFP will, in
coordination with the Nepali government and the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, utilize the proceeds from the sale of
empty bags and containers to fund and promote income-generating
activities and vocational training programs for the most needy
refugee families to encourage self-reliance, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were forced to flee Bhutan in 1989 and the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Seven rounds of ministerial meetings between Nepal and Bhutan
have been held but produced no result.
</P>
<P>
Bhutan agrees to take back only those of genuine Bhutanese
origin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
