<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Weapons Inspectors Return to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of 86 U.N. weapons
inspectors returned to Iraq on board a chartered plane Tuesday as
the latest Iraq-U.N. standoff over arms inspection was settled
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chartered plane carrying the inspectors landed at the
Habbaniya airport, 80 kilometers west of Baghdad, around noon
local time.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler last Wednesday
ordered the withdrawal of most of his staff in Baghdad, about 100
in total, on "strong recommendation" from U.S. government, which
said a military strike against Iraq was imminent.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference Monday in
New York that the U.N. Special Commission in charge of disarming
Iraq (UNSCOM) "is expected to resume its duty on Wednesday."
</P>
<P>
Eckhard also said that another six UNSCOM staff will return to
Baghdad on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a group of 30 U.N. humanitarian workers returned to
Baghdad on a U.N. flight to resume relief tasks in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 more U.N. humanitarian staff are expected to arrive
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq averted the U.S. and British air strikes at the last
minute by agreeing on Saturday to allow the resumption of
U.N. arms inspection unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, Iraq decided to ban UNSCOM and the International
Atomic Energy Agency from conducting field inspections of new
sites, but allowed monitoring activities to continue.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership took a step further on October 31 by
halting all cooperation with UNSCOM until the U.N. Security
Council moves toward the lifting of economic sanctions imposed
after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM
verifies that Iraq has come clean of all weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
