<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprises Play Important Part in Economic Activities: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua)-- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here on Tuesday that enterprises are the basic units
for economic activities and the carriers of capital and technology.
</P>
<P>
"Without the participation of enterprises, it would be
impossible for the economic and technical cooperation in the
Asia-Pacific region to develop dynamically," Jiang said at a
dialogue between the leaders of APEC member economies and the
representatives from the APEC Business Advisory Council (ABAC).
</P>
<P>
During the 80-minute dialogue which was convened by Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and attended by 63 ABAC
representatives, the two sides tried to find solutions to the
financial crisis and other economic issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
In his opening remarks, Mahathir said that the APEC (the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum) meeting this year is held
in an environment when most of the member economies have been hit
by financial chaos and are striving to recover their vitality.
</P>
<P>
He said that the most urgent task for now is to "restore the
investors' confidence" and to urge member economies to contribute
to rebuilding the world and regional economy.
</P>
<P>
During the first session of the two-session dialogue, the
business representatives focused their questions or remarks mainly
on ways to help the member economies and international
corporations walk out of the shadow of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was the first of the
leaders to respond. He outlined the measures Japan has taken to
deal with the crisis and the joint initiative with the United
States to stimulate Asian growth and recovery.
</P>
<P>
Vice President of the United States Al Gore expressed gratitude
to other members for the "hard efforts" they have made for dealing
with the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Gore also called for a reform of the international financial
architecture.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Chiang Pin Kung of
Chinese Taipei, Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung also spoke at the dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
