<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Probes Alleged Links With Sri Lankan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has pledged
to investigate into allegations that Sri Lanka's rebel Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) may have links with government
officials and other people in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Intensive investigations into the allegations have been
launched, Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo told reporters after
meeting with his Sri Lankan counterpart Lakshman Kadirgamar in
Pretoria Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We will investigate very intensively any contact between our
people and the LTTE," the Citizen newspapers Tuesday quoted Nzo
as saying.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was looking at introducing legislation in line
with international law preventing terrorist organizations from
setting up base in the country, Nzo told reporters.
</P>
<P>
LTTE fighting for a separate state had reportedly embarked on
a practice of ethnic cleansing by forcing all Muslims out of
their territory.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar pleaded with the South African government not to
encourage the "ruthless terrorist group" to operate from its
soil.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan foreign minister said he was at pains to spell
out to Nzo the terrible violence the LTTE had been involved in,
describing their actions as possiblely the worst atrocities
committed during the century.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar said Nzo told him that South African President
Nelson Mandela had earlier made it clear that the LTTE would
never be allowed to set up base in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nzo and Kadirgamar also discussed the expansion of relations
between the two countries, particularly the development of
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two-way trade of the two countries in 1997 totaled 253
million Rand (50 million U.S. Dollars).  
</P>
