<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's ASEAN Seat to Be Decided at Hanoi Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's entry into the
Association of Southeast Asian Nation (ASEAN) will be decided at
the ASEAN summit to be held in Hanoi next month, Malaysian
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Cambodia's admission into the nine-member regional
grouping would depend on the developments in the country between
now and the formation of a legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
"After the government has been formed, ASEAN member nations
will make an objective assessment of the situation and a report
will be submitted to the heads of government," he told reporters
after an ASEAN Consultation Council meeting here chaired by
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
He said the ASEAN leaders agreed unanimously at the meeting
that they should "wait and see" whether a government could be
formed in Cambodia before deciding on its entry.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial that a legitimate government is formed first,"
he said, adding that ASEAN had not set a deadline for Cambodia to
join the grouping.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the leaders also expressed their appreciation to
Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk for his mediation efforts between
Prime Minister Hun Sen and Prince Norodom Ranariddh to form a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia was not admitted to the ASEAN along with Myanmar and
Laos last year due to political uncertainties in that country.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
