<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Calls for Ecological Protection of Wadden Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature
(WWF) on Tuesday called on countries bordering the North Sea to
declare the Wadden Sea "a particularly sensitive sea area" in
order to avoid an ecological disaster caused by oil leak.
</P>
<P>
The oil spill, occurred last month, is threatening the highly
vulnerable mud flats in the Wadden Sea National Parks where about
20,000 oiled seabirds and waders have been recorded, said the
Switzerland-based conservation organization in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The fuel leak is also putting a proposed harbor porpoise
sanctuary and a grey seal colony at stake, the release added.
</P>
<P>
"The oil spill is an ecological disaster for Europe's largest
coastal wetland," said Stephan Lutter, head of WWF's North-East
Atlantic Program.
</P>
<P>
"There are too many loopholes in international ship safety
regulations and salvage procedures," Lutter said.
</P>
<P>
"It clearly runs against common sense that protective and
salvage measures cannot be imposed on a vessel in the vicinity of
a highly sensitive and vulnerable eco-region like the Wadden Sea,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
WWF proposes a number of precautionary measures to be applied
to adjacent waters in order to safeguard the Wadden Sea eco-region
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In particular, shipping regulations such as the salvage
mechanisms and transboundary cooperation in case of emergencies
need to be tightened up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
