<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Customs Revenue Declines Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's revenue
collection from customs duties registered a shortfall of 20
percent during the first quarter (July to September) of the
1998-99 fiscal year when compared with the corresponding period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Besides customs duties, revenue collection from the sales tax
and the excise duty also witnessed a declining trend during the
quarter, according to sources from the Central Board of Revenue
(CBR) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The only improvement was recorded in the collection of direct
taxes, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The CBR collected 14.7 billion rupees from customs duties
during the quarter, a drop of 20 percent as compared with the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the decline was partially due to
excessive rebates/refunds and chiefly due to the erosion of the
tax base in terms of decline in imports to the extent of 6.67
percent.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection of 11.2 billion rupees from sales tax
during the first quarter of the current fiscal year fell short of
the quarterly target of 11.4 billion rupees, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The CBR made a final tax collection of 58.7 billion rupees (46
rupees equals one U.S. dollar) during the first quarter, 16.6
percent of the budget target of 354 billion rupees.
</P>
<P>
The gross collection during the first quarter, at 72.4 billion
rupees, was up by 2.3 percent as compared to the same period of
the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The net collection during the first three months of the current
fiscal year, however, dropped by 4.7 percent as compared with last
year, due to excessive refunds/rebates to help exporters improve
their cash flows together with the extension of the date for
filing income tax return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
