<HEADLINE> Chirac to Run for Presidency in 2002: Close Aide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 17 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
will be most likely the presidential candidate representing the
Gaullist movement and other central-right parties in the next
presidential election of France in 2002, said a close aide of
Chirac's on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Pons, president of "Association of Friends of Jacques
Chirac,"said in a radio interview that being "the best common
rule-maker of the (rightwing) opposition, "Chirac should be
"logically" the presidential candidate for 2002.
</P>
<P>
As for the cohabitation between Chirac and the leftwing
government of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, Pons said that it could
"go until the end of the term" of the president in 2002, unless a
major crisis forced Chirac to dissolve the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, who was elected president in May 1995, dissolved a
rightwing-dominated National Assembly in the spring of 1997 and
allowed the leftwing coalition to come to power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
