<HEADLINE> Turkish Businessmen Call for Ocalan's Extradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkish business leaders have
called on their Italian counterparts to make efforts for the
extradition of Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), the Daily News said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a letter to Italy's Trade Chamber Union
Chairman Danilo Longhi by the Union of Turkish Trade Chambers and
Commodity Exchanges, the Economic Development Foundation and the
Council of Foreign Economic Relations.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that Italian government has no reason "to
prevent the PKK leader, who has killed many innocent people, from
being extradited to Turkey."
</P>
<P>
"If Abdullah Ocalan is not extradited by Italy to Turkey, we
convey to our Italian counterparts that we, as the top official
representatives of the Turkish private sector, are determined to
review our economic and commercial relations with Italy and
boycott Italian goods," it said.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was arrested last Thursday in Rome by Italian police
after stepping off a plane from Moscow, where he sought refuge
after being forced to leave his longtime Syrian hideout last month
because of Turkey's pressure on Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Russia denied him asylum; Italy has still not decided whether
to grant him refuge.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish
state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey considers Ocalan a terrorist and the country's
most-wanted criminal, bluntly demanding his extradition to Turkey
for trial for those crimes he committed.
</P>
<P>
But Italy has vowed not to bow to pressure from Turkey, saying
it is up to the courts to decide on Ocalan's extradition.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Italy, which is the second largest
trading partner of Turkey in Europe, will suffer heavy economic
losses if Turkey really imposes economic sanctions on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting on Aid to Malawi to Convene in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Consultative Group (CG)
meeting on aid to Malawi will be held next month in Malawian
capital Lilongwe instead of the traditional venue of Paris,
Zambian newspaper Financial Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will have a wider involvement of the government
ministries and stakeholders, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent statement from the World Bank country
director for Angola, Malawi and Zimbabwe, Barbara Kafka, this
year's meeting is expected to have a special session on poverty
to include discussions on government's poverty alleviation, AIDS,
population and safety net strategies.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, the World Bank is going to hold a
briefing on the CG while donors participating in the meeting will
have a field trip to a number of different project sites in
Malawi.
</P>
<P>
A CG meeting is usually a gathering of developing countrys'
donors for the purpose of reviewing recent developments and
challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
The donors usually clarify at the meeting the level and nature
of their financial commitments for the coming year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
