<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Israel Bluffs than Baffles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Israel's decision Monday to
suspend its troops withdrawal from the West Bank should be
regarded more as a bluff than as a real attempt to stall the peace
process, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said he freezes the
implementation of the Wye accord until Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat publicly retracts latest vow to declare independence in May
next year and resort to armed struggle against Israel over
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He announced the decision to the parliament before it began
debate over the land-for-security deal he signed with Arafat last
month, which calls for a further 13 percent Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank in exchange for tougher Palestinian security
measures.
</P>
<P>
The move came a little unexpectedly, but not as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu faces strong opposition from hard-liners in his
coalition over the agreement. This has been demonstrated last
week when the accord was ratified by only a narrow majority in his
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The parliament is expected to approve the accord by a landslide
majority due to the support from the main opposition parties,
especially the Labor, which pledged to support the government for
the 12-week implementation period.
</P>
<P>
However, the Labor is at the same time continuing effort to
advance elections - its safety net for Netanyahu is on the Wye
accord only, and will not last long.
</P>
<P>
This signals problems ahead. Netanyahu would find it a better
choice to grab the approval of his rightist coalition partners,
although some of them have threatened to topple the government in
any no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
To this end, he had to make efforts to allay their anger over
the Wye accord, in which they said Netanyahu gave too much to the
Palestinians but got too little in return.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's remarks made in the last two days were a ready tool
Netanyahu could use to reach his goal.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader's move was somewhat unusual since he had
refrained from renewing pledges to declare Palestinian statehood
since Wye. But it was understandable, as some of Netanyahu's
maneuvers were.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also faced opposition over the accord back home,
including from his own Fatah movement.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of the accord, which calls for crackdown on
anti-Israeli violence, Arafat's government has virtually come into
antagonism with militant Islamic organizations such as Hamas and
the Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
Clashes have broken out between Arafat's security guards and
members of the Fatah movement over the search of illegal weapons,
which was also demanded by the accord. One Palestinian youth was
killed in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's statements, therefore, were seen mostly aimed at
pacifying the Palestinians. They also came as a response to
Netanyahu's repeated threats to annex parts of the West Bank and
to the Israeli delay in carrying out the agreement, which has
deepened frustration among the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Withdrawal suspended, but the Palestinians appeared to have
nothing to lose, at least for now. The first phase of the
withdrawal, slated for Monday, had already been postponed before
the war of rhetoric heated up in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
Israel had told the Palestinians that it would begin
redeployment later this week. There seems, therefore, still plenty
of time for accusation, criticism and then, explanation and
clarification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
