<HEADLINE> Typhoon-Hit Philippine Farmers Get Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
undertaken projects worth 548 million pesos (13.7 million U.S.
dollars) to help farmers recover from super typhoons, the
Philippines New Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Task Force on La Nina, through the Department
of Agriculture, has distributed corn and vegetable seeds and
post-harvest equipment to farmers affected by typhoons.
</P>
<P>
The task force would further help the farmers repair their
irrigation systems, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
William Dar, acting secretary of agriculture, was quoted as
saying these interventions were part of the ongoing aid program
of the task force.
</P>
<P>
Dar said in a report that two typhoons that hit the country
last month alone had caused 2.5 billion pesos (62.5 million
dollars) of loss in crops, fisheries and livestock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
