<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Develops First Hi-Tech Fault Finder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- An Australian university team
has developed a new hi-tech software "troubleshooter" which is the
world's first and may bring export sales worth 100 million U.S.
dollars in the next four years, its developers claim.
</P>
<P>
The software, the Astracon Connection Manager, was developed
over the last six years by CiTR Ltd., a software development
company owned by the University of Queensland in East Australia's
Queensland state.
</P>
<P>
CiTR Chairman Ted Edwards said the first software package had
recently been sold by the newly-established U.S.-based marketing
company Astracon Inc. to the giant U.S. telecommunications company
Bell Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Edwards said the Astracon Connection Manager simplifies
broadband data and Internet connections by monitoring network
status and enabling any faults it finds to be fixed speedily.
</P>
<P>
Such a product would be a boon to companies with extensive and
complex computer telephone systems, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
Rob Cook, Astracon's president and adjunct professor at
University of Queensland's faculty of computer science and
electrical engineering, said no system or software was available
at present that would simply make an electronic connection between
one point and another anywhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
"That's what our software aims to do," Cook told the Australian
Associated Press Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Somebody will be able to plug a computer into the wall, say 'I
want a connect to my favorite web provider' and the connection
will automatically happen."
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications companies and Internet service providers
would find the product particularly useful, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Connection Manager would also help companies such as U.S.
giant AT&AMP;T avoid the relay problem that "browned out" its whole
network a year ago, affecting millions of customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
"They couldn't quickly find out who those customers were and
how they were impacted," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our software will immediately notify the service provider that
the fault has happened, that it has impacted connections of
various customers and allowed the service provider to correct
those problems almost in real time."
</P>
<P>
Astracon Inc., based in Denver, a city in the state of
Colorado, the United States, was established by the University of
Queensland, which holds a 35-percent stake, as a marketing company
to attract American venture capital.
</P>
<P>
Astracon would market and develop the product in the United
States but the technology base would remain in Queensland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
