<HEADLINE> Malaysian FM Criticises Gore's Provocative Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign
Minister Ahmed Badawi on Tuesday rejects as most unwarranted the
provocative remarks made by U.S. Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
Gore said here on Monday night at a dinner party attended by
over 1,000 Malaysian government officials and industrial leaders
that those who were involved in the reform movement launched by
former Malaysian deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim were the
"brave people of Malaysia".
</P>
<P>
Gore is here to deputize President Bill Clinton at the 6th
informal leaders meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) on November 17-18.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia views the remarks as a gross interference in the
internal affairs of the country and a brazen violation of the
basic tenets governing the relations between sovereign states,"
Badawi said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia finds the incitement by the U.S. government to
lawlessness by certain elements within the country to use
undemocratic means in order to overthrow a constitutionally
elected government."
</P>
<P>
"The action by the U.S. patently is not to advance the cause of
democracy and the rule of law but to serve its own narrow
political agenda," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some other Malaysian ministers also criticised
Gore's remarks and urged Gore to withdraw his remarks. They said
the remarks had spoiled the mood of the APEC meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
