<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Studying Consultations Between Lozis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
studying the consultations between the Caprivian Lozi separatists
in northeastern Namibia and Lozis from the Barotseland Province
of Zambia, the Zambian government spokesman has said.
</P>
<P>
Chief government spokesman Newstead Zimba said here Monday
that the government is studying a statement issued by the leader
of oppositon Agenda for Zambia (AZ) led by Akashambatwa
Mbikusita-Lewanika on the links between the two countries' Lozis,
the Times of Zambia reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lewanika, who has been advocating the secession of the
Barotseland, said Monday that the Caprivian Lozis and those from
the Barotseland were "one people".
</P>
<P>
The opposition party leader, who admitted meeting the Namibian
Lozis, even argued that the Caprivian secessionist movement led
by Mishake Muyongo, president of Namibia's largest opposition
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, had the right to decide whether to
"rejoin" a free Barotseland, enjoy self-rule or remain in
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Zimba said that the remarks by the AZ leader regarding links
with the Caprivian Lozis who were considered rebels in their own
country were serious and needed careful scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
"We have read the statement issued by Mbikusita-Lewanika, but
I can not give a reaciton just now because we are studying both
the statement and the situation at the moment", Zimba said.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, a Namibian newspaper, The Namibian, reported that
top figures in the Caprivi movement fighting for secession from
that country were now forging an alliance with Lozi separatists
in the Barotseland.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report from the United Nations Humanitarian
Information Unit (IRIN) said that in the last two weeks, over 400
Caprivian separatists had fled Namibia to neibouring Botswana to
seek refuge.
</P>
<P>
And in a national address at the weekend, Namibian President
Sam Nujoma demanded that Botswana repatriates the separatists to
face charges of treason and murder.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government had since ordered security sweeps in
the northeastern area by the army and para-military Special Field
Force, IRIN said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
