<HEADLINE> Mahathir Urges APEC Leaders to Focus on Asia's Economic Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad on Tuesday stressed the need for the leaders of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) to focus on the
current economic chaos in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The currency trading and other short-term capital flows have
caused social and political instability, said Mahathir while
meeting with his Japanese counterpart Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, who shared the view, called for the disclosure of
short-term investment funds. He said it is "important to seek
disclosure of such funds," a Japanese official said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir has repeatedly blamed hedge funds and other
speculative investors for causing the prolonged financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The regional chaos is on the top agenda of the 6th APEC
informal leaders meeting which will begin here later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
APEC, which was formed in 1989, has 21 members -- Australia,
Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong of China, Indonesia,
Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New
Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Singapore, Chinese Taipei,
Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
