<HEADLINE> APEC Leaders Bustle About Bilateral Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of APEC members
who are here for the annual APEC Leaders Meeting on Tuesday have
been trying to make most of their time through hectic bilateral
talks.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad on Monday spent eight
hours meeting eight leaders at the Palace of the Golden Horses,
the main venue for Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, Mahathir met South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung, Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, Chiang
Pin-Kuan from Chinese Taipei and Australia Prime Minister John
Howard.
</P>
<P>
He spent the afternoon meeting with Sultan of Brunei Muda
Hassanal Bolkiah, Philippine President Joseph Estrada, Peruvian
President Alberto Fujimori and Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for the leaders of Australia, the
Philippines and South Korea to meet Mahathir since the region was
plunged into a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The leaders discussed a spectrum of issues including APEC
matters, the financial crisis in Asia, political issues and
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his meeting with Kim, Mahathir said the South
Korean president hoped that Malaysia would continue its "Look East
Policy".
</P>
<P>
South Korea viewed the policy as a good mechanism to lift the
region out of the current economic predicament.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he had raised the issue of Anwar's arrest in his
lengthy discussion with Mahathir. He said Mahathir made an
explanation on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was not the only leader who had a very tight
schedule. Chinese President Jiang Zemin spent more than six hours
holding talks with five leaders.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Jiang is scheduled to meet Philippine President
Joseph Estrada, Indonesia President Jusuf Habibie, Singaporean
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley in the morning and Mahathir and Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov in the afternoon. 
</P>
