<HEADLINE> Kenya to Revise Civil Service Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will
revise the code of regulations for civil service to effectively
fight corruption and other malpractices, a senior Kenyan official
has said.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Principal Administrative Secretary in the Office of the
President, Solomon Boit, said here Monday that the government is
determined to enhance good governance in the country and was
finalizing a more supportive code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
The government has also intensified the computerization
process to improve efficiency and inventory of public assets,
accountability and service delivery, Boit said during the
official opening of Computer Application to Data and Office
Management courses for Attorney-General's Chambers staff.
</P>
<P>
He said the computerized system, called Intergrated Payroll
and Personnel Database (IPPD), will integrate three functional
areas -- Complement Control, Payroll Administration and Personnel,
Budgeting.
</P>
<P>
"The IPPD system has been piloted in seven ministries and will
soon be rolled out to all others," Tuesday's East African
Standard quoted Boit as saying.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi also told
permanent secretaries at the State House that the public servants
should make more efforts to enhance the efficiency and avoid to
be used as rubber stamps in projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
