<HEADLINE> Italian Foreign Minister Calls for Europe's Own Defense Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 16 (Xinhua) -- European countries should create
a defense agency of their own within the framework of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dini made the call at the opening ceremony of a two-day Western
European Union (WEU) foreign and defense ministers meeting, at
which the representatives from 18 WEU countries will discuss
defense cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Dini, whose country serves as the current rotating presidency
of WEU, said that while NATO is vitally important in protecting
the security of Europe, the continent itself should play a greater
role in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He said that European countries should establish a European
defense and security pillar within the NATO framework, which will
enjoy independent decision-making powers.
</P>
<P>
Dini emphasized that in addition to the monetary and economic
factors, political considerations should also constitute a very
important component of European integration.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the opening ceremony, NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana welcomed the progress European countries have made
in establishing a European defense and security pillar.
</P>
<P>
WEU comprises 10 members, five observers and three associate
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
