<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Russian Frontier Guards Jointly Control Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harbin, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese frontier guards in
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province recently joined hands with
their Russian counterparts in quelling illegal border crossings.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese guards discovered clues that the management staff
of a Russian market was forging fake transit visas and immediately
notified their Russian guards, who arrested members of the gang.
</P>
<P>
This particular event was one of the many cases in which Chinese
and Russian frontier guards have engaged in joint efforts to quell
illegal border crossings and smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"We most often exchange information by telephone, but on some
occasions we use signal flags," according to Shi Yejian,
director of the Heilongjiang Provincial Border Defence Bureau.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation and mutual assistance has enabled us to solve 288
cases of illegal border crossings, 2,800 criminal cases and a
large number of smuggling cases since 1991," said Shi.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang accounts for some 70 percent of the 4,300-km
border between China and Russia, the longest national border in
the world. Relations between the two countries has continued to
improve in recent years, with dozens of trading ports along the
border rapidly increasing trade and tourism.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in trade ports has also been accompanied by a
significant rise in entries and exits, as well as illegal border
activities such as smuggling," said Shi.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and Russian governments signed a border management
agreement to cope with related problems, with China's Ministry of
Public Security and Russia's Border Defence Administration
reaching an agreement calling for cooperation in dealing with
border affairs.
</P>
<P>
The joint efforts of frontier guards from the countries have
protected the order and stability in border areas.
</P>
<P>
"The current annual frontier trade volume stands 500 million US
dollars, and a large part of the achievement should be attributed
to sound cooperation between the frontier guards," according to
Guo Xiaohua, an official in Suifenhe, a small border town with a
population of less than 50,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
