<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Develops Programs for Disabled People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region has developed extensive programs for the
disabled over the past five years, according to officials with
Disabled Persons Federation of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 6,052 physically impaired Tibetans have
recovered from various disabilities since 1993. The regional
rehabilitation project has helped 5,926 cataract patients regain
their vision, offered treatment for 103 people suffering from
sequelae related to infantile paralysis, and provided linguistic
training which helped 23 deaf-mute children learn to speak.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has also supplied iodine pills to 2.02 million women in
order to prevent births of mentally defective children.
</P>
<P>
Disabled people have gradually realized the importance of
self-support, with over 3,465 handicapped individuals currently
operating private businesses.
</P>
<P>
Some 411 staffers work for welfare agencies under the region's
department of civil affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
