<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Positive to WTO Entry: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua)-- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here Tuesday that his country has adopted "a positive
attitude" toward the entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
WTO will be an incomplete international organization without
such a big developing country like China, Jiang said in a meeting
with New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley.
</P>
<P>
They are here to attend the 6th informal leaders meeting of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum between November
17-18.
</P>
<P>
"As a developing country to enter WTO, China's rights and
obligations must be balanced," Jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
China will take gradual steps to open its market in keeping
with its own practical conditions and what can not be done for the
time being can be accomplished after the entry, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that New Zealand is the first Western country to
have concluded an agreement with China on the latter's WTO entry,
which has helped boost the two countries' economic ties.
</P>
<P>
"China and New Zealand have become important trade and
investment partners," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said she is happy with her country's relations with
China. The exchanges of visits by leaders of the two countries
have promoted mutual understanding and bilateral relations, she
added.
</P>
<P>
She also reiterated that New Zealand will stick firmly to the
one-China policy, which has been deep-rooted in her country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
