<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Government Pledges to Help Rural-Based </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
assist local and foreign entrepreneurs to set up plants in rural
areas in an effort to increase Zimbabwe's production bases and
foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
A wider export base will enable local companies to import
capital goods and modernize their plants, Zimbabwean Minister of
Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira said at the opening of a
three-day workshop on the promotion of integrated rural-based
projects here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rural areas have to be developed so that they can become
markets for export, not only to remain as retailer outlets at
present, Tuesday's Herald newspaper quoted Shamuyarira as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Zimbabwe's domestic market has only 14
million people, hence it's necessary to find other markets for
export.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhiule, the rural areas can also be expected to create
employment for the thousands of unemployed people around the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government is exploring opportunities which
local companies can take advantage of, including existing markets
with neighboring countries like South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The government recognized the need to ratify the Southern
African Development Community trade protocol, explore the
European market and find ways to include new players into all
industries.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that we add as much value as we can to our
products, and the companies who source raw materials from the
rural areas should set up their bases there and take advantage of
the resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
The concept of promoting rural-based projects should increase
the participation of rural areas in creating wealth for the
country, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the export processing zones
authority, reportedly will also look at opportunities in the
European vegetable market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
