<HEADLINE> Bond Issuance Can Help Bring About Economic Recovery: APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The Business Advisory
Council of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) has
recommended the issuance of bonds as one of the ways to help
overcome the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The council, which ended its meeting here Tuesday, said that
affected economies could issue bonds to be guaranteed by stronger
economies to raise funds and help their recovery, an official who
attended the meeting said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The council proposed the Collaterized Bond Obligations plan at
the APEC ministerial meeting last Sunday as a means to encourage
long-term capital flows into the region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in conjunction with the on-going APEC meetings here
also discussed two projects under the Partnership for Equitable
Growth: the ASEAN gas grid and the information technology
application in small and medium scale enterprises and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
The 10th APEC ministerial meeting, which was held here on
November 14-15, was a preparatory meeting for the 6th informal
meeting of APEC leaders which will begin here later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
APEC, which was formed in 1989, has 21 members -- Australia,
Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong of China, Indonesia,
Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New
Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Singapore, Chinese Taipei,
Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
