<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Impose New Taxes for Rebuilding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A bill to obtain 2 billion taka
(about 41.2 million U.S. dollars) by levying new taxes to get
funding for post-flood rehabilitation was passed by the
Bangladeshi Parliament Monday night, The Financial Express daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kibria piloted the Post-Flood
Rehabilitation (Internal Resource Mobilization) Bill 1998 to
ratify the extra-budgetary fiscal measure.
</P>
<P>
The new taxes are for "symbolic participation" of the people in
the flood-rehabilitation program, alongside external aid, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
"This amount will not bring about any big change, but it has a
wide significance in that the donors would be convinced that the
people here are also ready to face this terrible flood, thus
enhancing the country's image abroad," he told the house.
</P>
<P>
The additional tax would not affect common people since the
surcharges are being levied on E-mail, fax, phones and savings, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The bill was based on proposals approved by the cabinet on
October 19.
</P>
<P>
Additional revenue will be made by imposing a 5-percent tax on
telex, fax, telephone and E-mail bills; a 2-percent tax on the
interest or profit from savings certificates; and a 2-ercent tax
on the interest and profit of fixed and periodical deposits in
banks and other financial institutions. Also to be imposed are 100
taka (about 2.06 dollars) on all documents for registry
irrespective of valuation; a 4-percent additional supplementary
tax on those imported items which are already under the purview of
supplementary tax excepting certain items; and a 15-percent tax on
the fees for the issue and renewal of passports.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh this year experienced the worst floods in a century,
which gripped about two-thirds of the country for two and half
months and seriously affected more than 30 million people,
inflicting a preliminary estimated loss of about 4.3 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
