<HEADLINE> Support for NZ Ruling Party Remains Low in Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny
Shipley has failed to narrow the gap in support rates in polls for
her
National Party, the ruling party, and the Labor party, the major
opposition party in the country, since she became prime minister a
year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The National Party rated 32 percent in the TV3/CM poll taken
from
November 10 to 15, compared with 31 percent in October last year
under
ousted prime minister Jim Bolger, the Dominion reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was down three percentage points from the previous TV3/CM
poll,
taken between September 8 and 13, the Wellington-based newspaper
added.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party was well ahead on 49 percent support in the
latest
poll.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll results, the Labor Party with 49 percent
votes
plus the votes it gets from minor parties with less than five
percent of
the national vote, could have as many as 62 of the Parliament's
120 seats
to the National Party's 40.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that Shipley's personal rating was 15
percent,
the lowest since she became prime minister and six percentage
points down
from September.
</P>
<P>
Helen Clark, leader of the Labor Party, rose one percentage
point to
24 percent since September.
</P>
<P>
On New Zealand's economic outlook for the next three months, 49

percent of the 1,000 eligible voters surveyed predicted a
deterioration
and 68 percent picked a rise in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The poll's margin of error was 3.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
