<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Fewer Births </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Fewer New Zealanders were
born in
the past year, Statistics New Zealand figures show.
</P>
<P>
In a media release issued Tuesday, Statistics NZ said there
were
56,353 live births in the year to September 30, a decrease of 963
from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The drop was partly because of a decrease in the number of
women of
child-bearing age, and partly because fewer of those women wanted
to be
pregnant, it added.
</P>
<P>
The annual birth rates showed that on average, New Zealand
women were
giving birth to 1.94 children, compared with the average of 1.96
children
in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure was below the level of 2.1 children needed
for the
population to replace itself without migration, the release said.
</P>
<P>
During the same period fewer New Zealanders died. Registered
deaths
totaled 26,679, down 670 from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Because the live births fell by a greater margin than deaths,
the gap
between births and deaths, called the natural increase of the
population,
narrowed by one percent, dropping from 29,967 in 1997 to 29,674 in
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
