<HEADLINE> New Zealand Exports More Wool to Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's wool fiber
exports to continental Europe increased 42 percent to 37,830 tons
in the year to September from 26,600 tons two years ago, the New
Zealand Wool Group said in its publication Wool Market, which was
released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Continental Europe is defined as the five countries of Germany,
 France, Italy, Belgium and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, Britain, a major market for New
Zealand's wool, imported 26,700 tons of wool fiber during the same
 period. This was up 48 percent from 18,050 tons in the year to
September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Wool Market said that the increase in exports to
continental Europe in the past two years reverses a long-term
decline in NZ wool fiber direct exports to that part of the world.
From a peak of 76,000 tons in 1984-1985, wool exports to that
region fell to 27,600 tons in 1995-1996, a drop of 64 percent and
nearly 50,000 tons per annum.
</P>
<P>
"However, that trend now appears to have been reversed," it
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that New Zealand's total wool fiber exports in the
year to September were down "only marginally" in volume to
181,660 tons and down one percent in value to 904 million NZ
dollars (485 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
