<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increases Arable Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A revised version of China's
national land-use plan has put the country's total arable land at
128 million hectares, about 26.7 million hectares more than the
previous figure.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of Outlook magazine reported that the revised
overall land-use plan, drafted by the Ministry of Land and
Resources, is soon to be submitted to the State Council for
examination and approval.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which is designed to curb decreases in arable land,
sets specific requirements for the possession of arable land, the
scale of basic farmland and the land available for construction.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the occupation of high quality arable land, the
ministry has stipulated that the basic farmland should account for
80 percent of related land in most regions, with the portion for
developed coastal areas raised to over 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
China also plans to transform more than 33,000 hectares of
reclaimed land into lakes and another 2.67 million hectares into
forests and grassland in where desertification has emerged.
</P>
<P>
The arable land planned as such will ensure the country's grain
supply given the big population in China, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
