<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Students Shoulder Heavy Study Burdens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Students in the east China
municipality of Shanghai continue to shoulder heavy study burdens
in spite of local government efforts to reduce the workload.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of 300 primary and secondary school students
revealed an average 6.7 daily class periods lasting 45 minutes
each, with 80 percent of them spending an additional 1.6 morning
or afternoon class periods for individual study.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that students spend an average two
hours per day on homework, excluding extra work assigned by their
parents.
</P>
<P>
Some 87 respondents indicated their parents hired tutors for an
additional 1.2 class periods per week.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of students pointed to the start of their day
at 06:00 in the morning and noted they went to bed at 21:00 in the
evening. Most senior high school students slept between 6-7 hours
per day.
</P>
<P>
"I leave home before 07:00, return at 17:00 and then do my
homework. A long day of study leaves me exhausted," said one
student.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
