<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Urges Political Parties to Join "Forward March" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina has urged political parties and people irrespective
of shades of opinion to join in the nation's "forward march" for
attaining economic emancipation, an English daily newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is time that all should work for building the nation," she
said in reply to "an ovation" from her cabinet colleagues on
Monday at a closed-door meeting, right after the regular cabinet
meeting was over, The Bangladesh Observer quoted reliable sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The action by the prime minister was taken after she announced
Sunday that the ruling Awmi League would never call hartal
(strike), "even it returned to the opposition."
</P>
<P>
Leaders of political parties have expressed different reaction
over Hasina's announcement. Some hailed it while others refrained
from giving any reaction.
</P>
<P>
Begum Khaleda Zia, leader of the major opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party and former prime minister, has refrained from
immediate reaction to Hasina's offer.
</P>
<P>
She told the ministers that "people's rights to vote freely has
been established and therefore hartal has become redundant," the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina directed officials to take integrated rural development
program for revitalizing the economy from the grassroots level to
accelerate the country's development.
</P>
<P>
She also asked them to draw up post-flood projects very fast
for getting speedy help from the donors.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has already received 756 million U.S. dollars for
relief and post-flood rehabilitation and reconstruction programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
