<HEADLINE> Indian Scientist Being Victimized for Opposing N-tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Several scientists have
joined hands to oppose a move to punish one of them who spoke out
against India's nuclear tests, The Statesman reported here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A senior scientist of the Institute of Mathematical Sciences is
being victimized at the behest of the Department of Atomic Energy
(DAE) for having spoken his mind, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The move to punish Dr T. Jayaraman of the Chennai-based
institute was provoked by two events -- a letter signed by many
theoretical physicists and supposedly organized by him, protesting
weaponisation in the South Asian region and an article written by
him in "Seminar", criticizing the tests conducted in May this
year.
</P>
<P>
In an e-mail sent to the scientific community, two scientists
from the universities of Cologne, Germany and New York asked
scientists around the world to petition the director of the
Institute of Mathematical Sciences in support of Dr Jayaraman.
They pointed out that action against him would be violative of
basic freedoms.
</P>
<P>
In India, scientists from the Tata Institute of Fundamental
Research, Mumbai, Indian Institute of Science, Bangalore and
Institute of Physics, Bhubaneswar, have taken the initiative.
</P>
<P>
Last week, scientists at the Tata Institute of Fundamental
Research held an emergency meeting on campus and decided to
"alert" all scientists in the country through e-mail, so that they
could send appeals, either individually or on behalf of their
institutions, to the institute in support of Dr Jayaraman.
</P>
<P>
E-mail being circulated in the scientific community in the
country lists chronologically the events which led to Dr Jayaraman
being "threatened with a job termination."
</P>
<P>
Dr Jayaraman, along with several other scientists of India
numbering over 75, was a signatory to a statement on May 18,
protesting against India's nuclear tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
