<HEADLINE> Thai Manufacturing Seen to Grow 4 Percent Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's manufacturing
sector next year is expected to grow by 4 percent because of an
increase in the export sector, particularly in electronics,
agriculture and light industries.
</P>
<P>
The trend in the real sector next year is expected to recover,
with a growth of more than 4 percent compared with a negative
growth this year, Chakramon Pasukvanich, deputy secretary of the
Board of Investment of Thailand (BOI), was quoted Tuesday by The
Nation as saying.
</P>
<P>
The growth in the manufacturing sector will help stimulate the
country's economic situation with positive growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
New investment next year will be seen in the electronics
industry as well as in the export sector of electronics and
agricultural products. There will be an expansion in existing
facilities of the BOI's projects to focus on export.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital will be injected through mergers and
acquisitions of Thai companies to solve the liquidity crunch, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The electronics sector will retain its major portion of the
country's exports. Car exports next year will jump from around
70,000 units to over 100,000 units. Apart from major car exporter
Mitsubishi, other car companies have started to emphasize exports,
including Toyota, Honda and Ford. BMW and Daimler Chrysler also
plan to use Thailand as their production base.
</P>
<P>
Potential agricultural products include canned seafood and
frozen chicken. There will be a slow growth trend for canned
pineapple and canned vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Light industries including footwear and garments will retain
their growth, but toys and jewelry will have negative growth.
</P>
<P>
Chakramon said steel and petrochemical industries next year
need to increase their exports to generate income to solve their
problem of debt burden and high interest repayment. The recovery
in the steel and petrochemical sectors also depends on debt
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Industries that focus on domestic consumption, including
construction and construction materials, will continue to face
negative growth and demand next year unless the government
approves a budget for infrastructure projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
