<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More NLD Members Resign in Myanmar: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 232 members of five
township branches of Myanmar's opposition National League for
Democracy (NLD) have resigned and five branches of the party have
dissolved since September, the official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NLD members, who resigned from the five township branches
in Rakhine, Mon, Kachin, Ayeyawady and Mandalay states and
divisions, are said to have made the move out of their own
volition since they had no desire to carry out the political
activities of the party.
</P>
<P>
The five NLD branches, which dissolved after September, include
three in Mrauk-U, Sittwe and Ponnagyun townships in remote western
Rakhine state and two in Thanpyuzayat and Bilin townships in
southern Mon state.
</P>
<P>
The NLD members and branches are said to have presented their
resignation and dissolution requests to their respective township
offices of the Multi-Party Democracy Election Commission formed to
supervise the general election held in May 1990.
</P>
<P>
However, the NLD headquarters based in Yangon, the capital
city, charged in a series of statements that the authorities have
been cracking down on the party, pressuring its detained members
to resign and some township branches to dissolve illegally and
forcibly.
</P>
<P>
It said in a statement that "it could not accept the
dissolution (of the branches) at all," adding that "as a branch of
the party, it has no right to do so without the knowledge of the
Central Headquarters."
</P>
<P>
It also said that the move goes against the Political Parties
Registration Law designed by the authorities concerned.
</P>
<P>
The NLD said that the authorities were "illegally" using people
from all walks of life who were under "pressure" to express the
"people's desire" and this created further political confusion.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed that it reserves the right to organize similar
mass rallies to present facts on the current situation in Myanmar
as a legal political party.
</P>
<P>
The NLD won the 1990 general election, contested by 93
political parties, with 396 parliamentary seats out of 485.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
