<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Tourism Continues to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's tourism
continued to drop during the first nine months of this year, with
78.6 million foreign tourists visiting the country, a figure down
2.9 percent from the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released Monday by the State Statistic
Bureau, September saw a decline of 8.5 percent in the number of
the foreign tourists visiting the country, while the number of
Czech citizens travelling abroad dropped 3.7 percent in the nine
months.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Czech tourism revenues fell 10.5 percent to 3.65
billion U.S. dollars from an unprecedented 4 billion dollars in
1996, when the number of foreign tourists hit a record high of
more than 100 million.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the share of tourism revenues in the gross domestic
product (GDP) sagged from 7.3 to 7 percent. Foreign trade
earnings also fell from 18.8 percent to 16.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Czech tourism, which is one of the country's backbone
industries and main sources of hard currency earnings, developed
rapidly from 1992, but started to fall in 1997 because of the
world economic turmoil and the poor quality of tourism services,
due especially to the financial crises in Southeast Asia and
Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
