<HEADLINE> APEC Should Stick to Economic Issues, Says Goh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong said here Tuesday that leaders who want to
bring up political issues should do so at bilateral meetings
rather than using the regional economic forum of APEC
(Asia-pacific economic Cooperation).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here after a bilateral meeting with Thai
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, Goh said that the regional economic
forum should stick to economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Goh was referring to a statement by U.S. Vice President Al Gore
on the "Reformation Movement" against the government launched by
former Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim after he was
dismissed in early September.
</P>
<P>
Gore said on Monday night at a dinner participated by over
1,000 government officials and captains of industry that those who
were involved in the "Reformation Movement" were the "brave people
of Malaysia."
</P>
<P>
Gore's remarks have been met with strong rebuke from Malaysian
government officials. Malaysian Works Minister Samy Vellu and the
International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz criticized
Gore for the remarks, saying it had spoiled the mood of APEC.
They urged Gore to retract the statement.
</P>
<P>
Gore is here to represent President Bill Clinton at the Sixth
APEC Economic Leaders' Informal Meeting on November 17-18.
</P>
</TEXT>
