<HEADLINE> Oil, Gold Prices Fall Sharply on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Oil and gold prices fell
sharply Monday on U.S. market after tensions between the United
States and Iraq eased without a military confrontation, according
to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
At the New York Mercantile Exchange, crude oil for December
delivery fell by 75 cents to 12.82 U.S. dollars a barrel, the
lowest since August 13. December heating oil fell by 1.71 cents
to 36.15 cents a gallon; December unleaded gasoline fell by 1.48
cents to 39.57 cents a gallon; and December natural gas fell by
15.4 cents to 2.305 dollars for each 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
World oil supplies have been swollen this year by
overproduction as well as weaker demand from once-booming East
Asia. But prices rose above 14 dollars a barrel last week as the
U.S. threatened to strike Iraq if the latter failed to cooperate
with the United Nation's arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices also ended lower after the crisis was defused. At
the New York Mercantile Exchange, December gold ended down 90
cents at 295.6 dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Market participants said as the threat of military action has
been averted, there seems no immediate need to buy the precious
metal against inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
