<HEADLINE> Italian, NATO Officials Satisfied Over Iraq's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema and Secretary General of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) Javier Solana on Monday expressed their
satisfaction over Iraq's decision to allow the resumption of
United Nations weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after meeting with Solana, who came here
for a West European Union summit scheduled to begin later Monday,
D'Alema said he and Solana hoped Iraq would now behave in
accordance with the decision announced by its leader, Saddam
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
During their discussions, the two leaders voiced satisfaction
because President Saddam has yielded to the U.N. requests,
official sources said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. weapons inspectors were ordered back to Iraq on Sunday
after its leader wrote to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
offering unconditional compliance with international demands.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's move averted an United States bombing offensive which
Italy had sought to avoid through diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema also said he discussed with Solana the issues of
NATO enlargement to the Southeast of Europe and Europe's role
in its own defence.
</P>
<P>
He said that the discussions produced "strong agreement" on the
alliance's objectives.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders are scheduled to meet for a summit next March
which will sanction the entry of Hungary, Poland and the Czech
Republic into the alliance. Italy wants this intake to be
followed quickly by other East European countries such as Romania
and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, D'Alema noted that Italy was already moving to
develop security ties on the southern fringes of Europe.
</P>
<P>
"I told the secretary general about Italy's commitment to
improving security in the Adriatic and the Ionian because
stability in this area is key to the security not only of Italy,
but also of Europe," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
