<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Export Value Likely to Increase Slightly Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to
achieve a slight growth in exports next year, from the estimated
57 billion U.S. dollars this year and 58 billion dollars last
year, according to Boontipa Simaskul, inspector-general of the
Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Boontipa declined to reveal the exact growth expected next
year, but said she believed growth was viable as export-related
problems, such as tight liquidity, were being resolved.
</P>
<P>
The government has implemented a range of measures covering
finance, loan assistance from overseas and debt restructuring, to
streamline the financial system and inject funds into the
manufacturing and export sectors, the Bangkok Post Tuesday quoted
Boontipa as saying.
</P>
<P>
Boontipa said government measures already implemented would
begin to bear fruit next year.
</P>
<P>
Government measures to aid exporters include action to reduce
production costs to increase the country's competitiveness,
industrial restructuring, encouraging exporters to find new
markets, and promotion of the export of value-added products.
</P>
<P>
"Those measures could stimulate the country's export activities
next year. If the world's economic and financial situation doesn't
worsen, Thai exports in dollar denominations will increase," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Boontipa said she recognized that exports in dollar terms would
fall by the end of this year but would improve in baht terms.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, Thailand's exports in
dollar terms were 40.624 billion dollars, down 5.6 percent from
the same period last year. In baht terms, exports totaled 1,700
billion baht, up 44.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
