<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Print Smuggling in China Getting Worse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The news print smuggling in
China is getting worse, China Light Industry News reports.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Guangzhou Customs seized 1,146
tons of smuggled news print worth 6.67 million yuan, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
Some companies in the United States, Canada, and the Republic
of Korea have sold news print abroad at lower prices, for as much
as 120 to 180 U.S. dollars per ton cheaper than in their own
countries.
</P>
<P>
That brought the average import price for every ton of news
print to 350 U.S. dollars in 1997, compared with 649 dollars in
1995. The standard international price in 1997 was 550 dollars.
</P>
<P>
It also pushed up news print imports in China to 356,000 tons
in 1996 from 49,000 tons in 1995. Imports continued to increase in
1997. And in the first seven months of this year, 7,272 tons of
news print entered China through Guangzhou, more than the total
imports for 1997 through that area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
