<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Astronomers Spot Advance Leonid Meteors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of Leonid meteors were
observed early Tuesday morning in the sky above Beijing, Nanjing
and Wuhan cities in eastern China, according to the Beijing
Astronomical Observatory (BAO) and the Nanjing Purple Mountain
Observatory.
</P>
<P>
"Some 100 meteors per hour were observed after midnight in
urban Beijing, with even more spotted by astronomers benefitting from
better conditions at the BAO Xinglong Station in Hebei Province,"
one BAO spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"I witnessed a number of fireballs, or shooting stars, which
were bright enough to illuminate the faces of observers at the
station," according to Zhu Jin, a leading astronomer for the
station's Leonid Meteor Storm (LMS) observations.
</P>
<P>
"I even saw a bright fireball as late as 07:00 this morning,"
said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers are more optimistic about conditions for viewing
the LMS early Wednesday morning following Tuesday observations.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 amateur stargazers in Beijing, along with 100
Chinese and foreign researcher, plan to watch the LMS early
tomorrow morning at the BAO's Shahe and Miyun stations in suburban
Beijing and at the BAO Xinglong Station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
