<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Maintains Life Sentences for Ex-Nazi Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 16, (Xinhua) -- The Court of Cassation, the high
court of Italy, maintained the life sentence verdict on two former
German Nazi officers Monday for their involvement in Italy's worst
massacre during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Erich Priebke, 84, a former Schutzstaffel captain, and Karl
Hass, a former major, were sentenced to life imprisonment by the
Italian court-martial on March 3.
</P>
<P>
Lawers of the defendants called for the repeal of the sentence,
arguing that the two former officers were merely carrying out
orders of their superiors.
</P>
<P>
The high court announced its decision after four and a half
hours of deliberations.
</P>
<P>
On March 24, 1944, German troops rounded up 335 Italians and
shot them dead in the outskirts of Rome in retaliation for the 33
German soldiers killed the day before in a bomb attack carried out
by Italian guerillas.
</P>
<P>
The execution -- 10 Italians for each German soldier killed --
was ordered by the German commandant in Rome, Major Herbert
Kappler, with the additional five victims shot because of a
clerical error made by Priebke.
</P>
<P>
Priebke was tracked down by a U.S. television network in May
1994 in Argentina and extradited to Italy one and a half years
later. Hass, who initially came to Rome as a witness, was found
guilty and arrested in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The victims' families supported the high court's decision, but
lawers for the two defendants said they would seek presidential
remission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants Gore to Retract Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Works Minister
S. Samy Vellu Tuesday asked U.S. Vice President Al Gore to retract
his statement supporting the anti-government "reformation
movement" in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Gore said at a dinner Monday night for over 1,000 government
officials and captains of industry from the Pacific Rim that the
people who had been involved in the "reformation Movement" were
the "brave people of Malaysia."
</P>
<P>
The "reformation movement" was launched by former Malaysian
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim after he was sacked early September.
</P>
<P>
Describing Gore's remarks as a "blantant interference in
Malaysia's internal affairs, Samy Vellu said that Gore's remarks
had irked many Malaysians.
</P>
<P>
Samy Vellu said Gore's statement was "a serious deviation from
the accepted principle of non-interference of one democratic
country into the internal affairs of another.
</P>
<P>
"His statement is uncalled for and unprecedented in the history
of Malaysia and of a vice president of the United States," Samy
Vellu said.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that a person holding the second highest
office in the U.S. and an experienced politician has fallen prey
to wrong advise," the Malaysian minister said.
</P>
<P>
Gore is here for the sixth informal meeting of Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) leaders on November 17-18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
