<HEADLINE> Situation in South China Sea Stable, Jiang Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, in a meeting with Philippine President Joseph Estrada here
here Tuesday, said that the overall situation in the South China
Sea is stable.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of China and the Philippines have reached important
common understanding on it, and the two countries will seek common
development in the region despite disputes, according to the
Chinese President.
</P>
<P>
"As we have agreed, we will leave aside the disputes and undertake
common development because safeguarding the stability and prosperity
of this region lies in the common interests of both of us and other
countries in this region as well," said the Chinese President.
</P>
<P>
As for the existing disagreement, Jiang said, it has been
China's consistent stand that to solve it properly through
friendly consultations according to international law and relevant
laws of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that the Philippines and China have a wide range
of common interests, and that both countries are making efforts to
boost the peace and prosperity of Asia. He expressed the hope to
maintain the friendly relationship of cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China and the Philippines are close neighbors.
China is willing to further expand the friendly exchanges and
cooperation between the two countries in all the fields, so as to
bring a stable, fully-developed bilateral relationship of mutual
trust and cooperation into the new century and make more
contributions to the stability and prosperity of the region.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who congratulated his counterpart for his being the
President of the Philippines, invited him to visit China at his
convenient time.
</P>
<P>
Both Jiang and Estrada are in Kuala Lumpur to attend the
6th APEC Leaders Meeting. 
</P>
