<HEADLINE> Shanghai Increases Timber Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has imported 17,000
cu.m. of timber since July, up 200 percent on the same 1997
period, with imports of plywood rising nearly 61 percent to
55,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The increase was attributed to the country's campaign against
smuggling in place since the national anti-smuggling conference
held in July.
</P>
<P>
The city's timber imports for the January-October period grew
77 percent on an yearly basis to top 192,000 cu.m., with the
volume for plywood rising 14.7 percent to 117,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
China has witnessed an increasing demand for timber due to the
damage resulting from this year's devastating summer flooding, and
measures introduced to prohibit logging in order to control soil
erosion.
</P>
<P>
Major timber importers such as Japan and the Republic of Korea
have reduced imports due to the financial crisis engulfing
Asia. On the other hand, however, major timber producers such as
Malaysia and Cambodia have increased timber exports to China in
order to offset losses resulting from the crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
