<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Beer Brewers Criticized for Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) --China's rapidly growing beer
business needs to tackle problems like overproduction and
packaging for healthier development, according to "China Light
Industry News."
</P>
<P>
The paper reports that, by 1997, China had gained a
24-million-ton capacity in its breweries and produced almost 19
million tons of beer last year.
</P>
<P>
But, although output went up, average earnings per ton dropped
50 yuan from the 1996 level, and this year about 50 percent of the
breweries are losing money.
</P>
<P>
China is now No.2, after the United States, in beer output in
the world. It is estimated that the country's beer output will
exceed 20 million tons by next year, so developing the market
through more market research while controlling production
capacity is essential, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
It suggests that more groups, lead by famous brands, be
established. China had 550 breweries by 1997, only 50 of which
belonged to conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
A greater effort needs to be made to improve quality, develop
new products, and increase environmental protection awareness, the
paper concludes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
