<HEADLINE> Peru, Bolivia to Build Pipeline to Transport Liquefied Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Peru and Bolivia will sign an
agreement in December on the construction of a pipeline to
transfer liquefied gas from La Paz in Bolivia to the docks of the
Peruvian port of Ilo, press reports said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline, measuring 420 kilometers, will extend over 300
kilometers in Peru and 120 kilometers in Bolivia, Bolivian
Ambassador to Peru Jorge Gumucio said in Monday's newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Gumucio said a memorandum on the pipeline had been signed last
March. The total cost of the project is estimated at between 100
and 120 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said the final agreement would be signed in the
second week of December during Bolivian President Hugo Banzer's
trip to Peru.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia also wants Peru to give it a concession to build
maritime installations to the south of the port of Ilo so that
Bolivia will be able to sell its liquefied gas abroad and in Peru.
</P>
<P>
During his trip, Banzer is expected to reiterate his support
for the joint infrastructure programs in Ilo which were agreed on
by the two countries back in 1992, including an unfinished highway
between La Paz and the port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
