<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Priceless Sri Lankan Bronze Statue Stolen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A priceless Sri Lankan
artifact, the Thara Devi bronze statue dating back to the 5th
century BC, has been stolen from the Anuradhapura Archaeological
Museum in North Central Province, according to reports reaching
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This happened in a spate of similar thefts of artifacts and
vandalism of historic archaeological sites.
</P>
<P>
Although the security guards who were on duty have been
arrested by the police, no further headway has been made. It has
not been established when and how it disappeared, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The missing statue was kept in a glass case with similar other
statues. The statue was found missing by a guard last Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The statue in a sitting position is three and a half inches in
height and two and a half inches in width.
</P>
<P>
The police suspect that this priceless statue had been smuggled
out of the museum, police sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The museum is open to the public every day from 8 a.m. to 5:45
p.m. There are about 15 guards for each section.
</P>
<P>
After the museum closes for the day the security guards are
expected to check every artifact and inform the officer in charge
of the museum. The keys are then handed over to police custody,
the sources explained.
</P>
<P>
Anuradhapura, over 200 kilometers from Colombo, is capital of
North Central Province. This ancient capital is foremost among the
Buddhism sacred cities in the country, dating back 2,500 years
with a glorious past of culture and heritage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
