<HEADLINE> Lhasa Develops Compulsory Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China and the United Nations
Children's Fund have provided substantial funding to improve
compulsory education in southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Some 8.1 million yuan (976,000 US dollars) from the regional
government, 1.22 million yuan from the United Nations Children's
Fund and 820,000 yuan from the Tibetan Children's Fund and Tibetan
Work Committee for Children and Women has been used to open dozens
of entertainment centers for children and women in a number of
cities and counties, including Lhasa, Xigaze, Qamdo, Qagqu and
Nyingchi.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope has constructed 110 primary schools in 60-odd
counties, with 10,000 local drop-outs receiving assistance to
resume their education.
</P>
<P>
The Spring Bud Project has used 2.25 million yuan to offer 22
classes for girls in 18 counties, and has helped more than 1,100
girls return to school.
</P>
<P>
Tibet had 814 primary schools and 3,314 teaching centers by the
end of Autumn this year, with compulsory education introduced to a
number of cities and counties, including Lhasa, Quxur, Gyaze and
Yadong.
</P>
<P>
The region's primary school enrollment stands 310,000, with the
entry rate hitting 81.3 percent. In addition, more than 32,000
students attend secondary schools which have an entry rate of 25
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
