<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Troops Sent to Destroy Opium Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has sent troops and
Border Patrol Police to destroy opium plants in mountainous areas
of the golden triangle before the harvest.
</P>
<P>
The target is to destroy up to 60 percent of plants cultivated
on 10,000 rai (1,600 hectares) of land in Chiang Mai, Mae Hong
Son, Tak, Chiang Rai and Phayao provinces, northern Thailand, the
Bangkok Post Tuesday quoted Lt. Gen. Sommai Vichavorn, commander
of the Third Army Region, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hilltribe people who grow poppy have introduced modern
technology which allows for year-round cultivation and improved
yields, he said.
</P>
<P>
Destroying the crop is time-consuming and labor-intensive
because the plants are being grown in small plots over a wide
area, he said.
</P>
<P>
Maj. Gen. Sirichai Suwansiri, director of Northern Narcotic
Prevention and Suppression Coordinating Center, said there were
2,000 rai (320 hectares) of poppy in Mae Hong Son province. So far
only 200 rai (32 hectares) had been destroyed, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
