<HEADLINE> More Chinese Join Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The family of Hong Xiujuan
in south China's Guangzhou city regularly surf the Internet to
find information used for a variety of purposes.
</P>
<P>
The Internet has enabled the family to regularly contact
friends and relatives living abroad, in addition to helping her
remain abreast of the the latest developments in academia.
</P>
<P>
"I've been using downloaded computer programs to teach my
daughter English, and she's learning quite fast." said Hong.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese families with good educational backgrounds are
accessing the Internet, with some 10 percent of the over 300,000
Guangzhou families with computers currently surfing the net.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 45 newspapers and television stations have
established homepages, including Xinhua News Agency, the People's
Daily and China Central Television (CCTV).
</P>
<P>
Chinese children who formerly opted for computer games are now
using systems to search for information. Computers have also
emerged as useful tools for locating jobs, conducting business,
purchasing or selling stocks, and accessing electronic newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China currently has 1.5 million registered
Internet users, with the number expected to hit five million users
by the end of the century. Chinese computer users will thus emerge
as an important consumer force in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
