<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Launch Joint Initiative to Help Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Japan launched a joint initiative here Monday night to help Asian
nations affected by the economic crisis obtain financing to revive
their banking systems and remove obstacles to restructuring.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time since the crisis which began in July
1997 that the United States has come forward to help the troubled
economies.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vice President Al Gore, who is here representing President
Bill Clinton to attend the 6th APEC Leaders Meeting, said the
initiative, known as the Asian Growth and Recovery Program (AGRP),
would be implemented with the help of Asian Development Bank and
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Gore announced this at the APEC Business Summit dinner at the
Putra World Trade Center in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Both countries and the two banks are working together to
mobilize five billion U.S. dollars initially to help private
financing for countries in the region which have put comprehensive
restructuring program in place.
</P>
<P>
The AGRP consists of four main components which are
accelerating the pace of bank and corporate restructuring;
increased trade finance to give Asian companies greater access to
funds needed to revive production and create jobs; efforts to
mobilize new private sector capital to help Asian companies
rebuild their balance sheets; and, enhancing technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
Details of the program will be finalized in a meeting in Tokyo
next month, bringing together senior officials and technical
experts from the United States, Japan and other Asian economies
and multilateral institutions.
</P>
<P>
Gore said the financial crisis was not just about weakness in
particular nations. "It demands that we strengthen the operations
of the entire international financial system," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Vice President said it was urgent that greater transparency
and openness was brought into the international economic system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
