<HEADLINE> Kurds in Sofia on Hunger Strike Over Leader's Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Twenty Kurds were on the third
day of a hunger strike here Monday to protest against the arrest
of the outlawed Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) leader Adullah
Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
"Our protest will continue indefinitely," Said Sipan, a
representative of the strikers, was quoted by Bulgarian Telegraph
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Learning that Ocalan went on a hunger strike immediately after
his arrest at Rome airport on November 13, Kurds gathered at the
cultural and information center on Kurdistan in central Sofia and
followed suit, Sipan said.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that the Italian authorities release Ocalan or
grant him political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 100 Kurdish residents in Moscow and about
50 Kurdish leaders in the Armenian capital of Yerevan have also
been on separate hunger strikes since Saturday in support of
Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, some 700 Kurds reportedly marched through Yerevan to
the United Nations representative office to press for his release.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for Kurdish autonomy in
Turkey. Some 37,000 people have been killed in the 14-year-old
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was arrested in Rome on a Turkish warrant after stepping
off a plane from Moscow, where he had fled after being expelled
from Syria. Russia denied him asylum. Italy has yet to decide
whether to grant him refuge.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan has been put on trial in absentia in Turkey on charges
of leading a terrorist organization, threatening the country's
territorial integrity and ordering killings. The charges can
bring the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Kurds demonstrated in support of Ocalan in Rome
and in towns across Germany over the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
