<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Cracks Down on Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Local authorities in
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, have
investigated 78 cases during the ongoing anti-smuggling campaign
and confiscated goods valued at 51 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The smuggled goods include automobiles and parts, plywood,
mobile telephones, diesel fuel, detergents, VCDs and cultural
relics.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have also rectified the local vehicle parts market
by closing a dozen-odd underground assembly workshops and
confiscating more than 300 illegally assembled vehicles. The
city's household electric appliance market has also been placed
under stricter supervision.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou authorities have also closed 23 small refineries and
expanded patrols along the Pearl River in an effort to curb oil
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The local government reported the confiscation of 2,366 tons of
diesel valued at 3.5 million yuan in August and September alone.
