<HEADLINE> Romania Faces Rising Deficit With European Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania's trade deficit with
central and eastern European countries reached 1.011 billion
U.S. dollars in the first eight months of 1998, up 22 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Romanian national statistical committee, the
country's exports to the region totaled 571 million dollars in the
first eight months, down 12.8 percent from the same period of last
year. But its imports from the region increased by 6.7 percent,
hitting 1.582 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Romania's exports to the region accounts for 21
percent of the total export volume. Its imports from the region
make up 10.4 percent of the import volume.
</P>
<P>
Romania's trade with the region increased greatly after it
joined the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Romania has experienced a surplus of imports so far.
</P>
<P>
CEFTA was established in 1992, and its current members include
Poland, Czech, Slovak, Hungary, Slovenia, Romania and Bulgaria.
</P>
</TEXT>
