<HEADLINE> Expert Calls for End to Redundant Rural Power Grid Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 17 (Xinhua) -- Redundant construction in
China's vast rural area has a bad effect on the ability to improve
power grids and needs to be avoided, according to Zou Yanyu, an
economist with the Hunan Electric Company.
</P>
<P>
Zou told Xinhua today that the central government has listed
rural power grid construction as one of the infrastructure
priorities and will spend 130 billion yuan over the next three
years on this.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by Zou's company found that hundreds of millions
of yuan had been spent on redundant low-voltage substations and
transmission lines, most of which do not comply with provincial
government plans.
</P>
<P>
Zou said that this redundancy is a waste of funds and leads to
economic inefficiency, which in turn will drive power suppliers to
raise prices, and that this goes against the original reason for
investment, which includes cutting the price of electricity in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Sufficient local studies and planning should be done before
construction work takes place, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
