<HEADLINE> EU to Help Special Groups Use "Easy Euro" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
submitted its pilot projects to help special groups of people use
"easy euro" at the time of transition to the euro, the European
Commission said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said that for the first time they proposed the
projects for evaluating specific difficulties which may arise for
three target groups: the elderly, the socio-economically
disadvantaged, as well as the blind and persons with impaired
vision.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 working parties, each composed of 15 of these persons,
have been set up in Belgium, France and Italy, aiming to create
between now and mid-1999 a source of information and training on
the euro, based on their own experiences and work, adapted to
their needs, practices and their methods of expression and
communication, according to the commission.
</P>
<P>
This source, once established, will be made available to all EU
members. 
