<HEADLINE> Sika Does Fails in Attempt to Kill Twin Offspring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A Sika doe in a park in
northeastern China's Liaoning Province recently failed in an
attempt to kill her twin offspring, apparently for a better life.
</P>
<P>
The doe gave birth to twins, a male and a female, on November
11 at the Dalian Labor Park. An attendant discovered the new
arrivals on the morning of the second day and noted that the doe
was attempting to use her body to suffocate the twins.
</P>
<P>
The twins were separated from their mother and timely medical
treatment greatly improved their condition within a short
time. The male, the largest twin, was able to drink milk and his
body temperature rose somewhat. The female twin failed to
immediately respond to treatment.
</P>
<P>
According to the park's director, the breeding season of Sika
deer normally occurs in May or June, with most doe having only one
offspring. He noted a November birth was extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
He said the mother quite likely tried to kill the twins fearing
they would be unable to survive the cold winter and the lack of
milk.
</P>
<P>
Sika deer are listed as a first-class animals under state
protection. The park is home to 21 Sika deer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
