<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 16 members of
various anti-government armed groups in Myanmar laid down their
arms to surrender to the government in October, the official New
Light of Myanmar newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
These armed groups' remnants, including those from the ethnic
Kayin National Union (KNU), the All Burma Students' Democratic
Front (ABSDF) and the People's Liberation Front (PLF), "exchanged
arms for peace" with the government in different military command
areas.
</P>
<P>
While in armed opposition to the Myanmar government, the KNU
and the ABSDF reportedly operate on the Myanmar-Thai border.
</P>
<P>
In April, former KNU central committee member Phado Aung San
defected to the government side with more than 200 of his men in
Hpa-an, Kayin state.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1988, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed
groups in the country have made peace with the government.
</P>
<P>
The government said it still permits the turned-in armed groups
to retain their arms for "self-protection and area-defense."
