<HEADLINE> Surprising Graf Earns Berth in Tour Finale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But after beating 10 consecutive foes, including world No. 1
Lindsay Davenport of the United States and No. 2 Martina Hingis
of Switzerland, the 29-year-old superstar now has an eye on a
closer prize: the Chase Championships, which begin today in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Davenport and Hingis, who are locked in a down-to-wire fight
for the year-end No. 1 ranking, are the top seeds at the
16-player season finale.
</P>
<P>
Graf will play No. 3 Jana Novotana of the Czech Republic on
Tuesday in the first round. No. 5 Monica Seles of the United
States opens Wednesday against Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
Graf earned the final berth Thursday after Ai Sugiyama of
Japan lost at the Advanta Championships and No. 5 Venus Williams
of the United States withdrew because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
Graf won her second consecutive and 106th career title Sunday,
beating Davenport in the Advanta Championships final in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
"To be able to qualify for the Championships even though I
didn't play much this year is a big surprise," Graf said. "If you
had seen me four weeks ago, you would have said, "Wow how did
that happen?"
</P>
<P>
Graf's coach Heinz Gunthardt says: "Two weeks ago, I doubt if
she even thought about qualifying for the Chase. It just wasn't
something she aimed to."
</P>
<P>
Graf's recent winning spree undoubtedly became sweeter after
she beat former No. 1 Hingis Friday. When Hingis became No. 1
last year, the 18-year-old dismissed Graf as a challenger,
saying: "Steffi has had some results in the past, but it's a
faster, more athletic game now than when she player. She is old
now. Her time has passed."
</P>
<P>
Graf has been the women's tour's dominant player during her
16-year career. In 1988, she became the only player, man or
woman, to win the four grand slam. She also is the only player to
win each of the four grand slam event four times.
</P>
<P>
Her 21 grand slam titles is three shy of the record held by
Margaret Court. She also holds the record for career earnings
with 20,489,142 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
