<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Growth in Light Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 17 (Xinhua) -- China's light industry sector
grew by 9.9 percent during the first nine months of this year
compared to the same period last year, with the total output value
standing at 4,164.12 billion yuan, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
The sector's value-added hit 642.8 billion yuan, up 8.5 percent
on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the State Statistics Bureau indicated
increased output for 13 of 25 major light industrial products,
including air conditioners, soft drinks and vacuum cleaners.
</P>
<P>
Production fell for 12 products, including electric ovens, salt
and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
Customs figures show that the light industry sector exported
products valued at 40.43 billion US dollars, up 6.62 percent on
the previous year's same period. Substantial increases were
recorded for plastics products, household appliances, lighting
fixtures, and bicycles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Agree Belgian Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The idea, first mooted at the end of September, will see
Antwerp acting as a 'feeder' club to make it easier for United to
attract talented youngsters from outside the European Union to
Old Trafford.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United Secretary Paul Bastio told BBC Radio 5 Live
that the idea had developed following a meeting between the two
club chairmen in 1996.
</P>
<P>
United youngster Danny Higginbotham, a 19-year-old defender,
is already on loan at Antwerp and United manager Alex Ferguson
and director Maurice Watkins traveled to Belgium on Monday to
conclude a "memorandum of co-operation" between the clubs.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC on Monday, details of the financial
arrangement between the two clubs have not been revealed but
Bastio said: "Let's say that each side will bear the financial
burden according to its possibilities."
</P>
<P>
Current regulations mean the UK government will not grant work
permits to non-EU players unless they have been capped by their
country at senior international level and even then, will not
renew them unless a player appears in 75 per cent of a club's
games in the first season.
</P>
<P>
The scheme would see players spending two seasons in Belgium
to earn EU citizenship and then moving to United without
restriction.
</P>
<P>
"What we are hoping to achieve here is a co-operation with
Royal Antwerp which will work for the benefit of our respective
footballing businesses.
</P>
<P>
"It will enable us to have a look at players from outside the
European Union through the medium of the Antwerp team, whereas at
the moment we cannot look at players - particularly young players
-because of the immigration rules and Premier League rules," said
Watkins.
</P>
<P>
The two clubs will be able to play each other competitively in
Europe if drawn to face each other in future despite the link-up.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of that being a problem because
Manchester United would not be obtaining any interest in Royal
Antwerp, so there is no conflict with any of UEFA's rules and
regulations with regard to their competitions," Watkin added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
