<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, November 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will fly to Japan and
South Korea this week to resume his Asia trip after the Iraqi
crisis was defused, the White House said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at a Wednesday departure," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said at a news briefing. Details will be
announced later, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Clinton will be holding meetings with
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi on Japan's latest stimulus
plan and with South Korean President Kim Dae-jung on a host of
issues including the Korean Peninsula. He will also visit Guam in
the tour.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was scheduled to start the trip with the first leg to
Malaysia to attend an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
leaders meeting. But the first stop was skipped as he was to
monitor the crisis over U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq. Vice
President Al Gore replaced him at the APEC meeting.
(US-Clinton-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In a response to Israel's decision to suspend
implementation of further redeployment in the West Bank,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat insisted Monday night that the
Palestinians are committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
The pursuit of peace is the "strategic decision" made by the
Palestinians and should be the same goal for Israel, Arafat was
quoted by Israel Radio as saying.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in the West Bank town of Jerico before
meeting with the United States Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, who
is in the region to oversee the implementation of the
land-for-peace deal signed on October 23.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came hours after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu announced that he would suspend the withdrawal of
Israeli troops from the West Bank until Arafat publicly retracts
the statements vowing to declare independence next May and warning
Israel of possible resumption of Palestinian armed struggle.
(Palestinians-Israel-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Some 150 United Nations humanitarian workers left here
Monday for Baghdad to resume their tasks in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The return came two days after Iraq agreed to unconditionally
resume cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors and the United States
temporally withdrew its military menace.
</P>
<P>
About 120 of the U.N. workers departured on four Iraqi buses
and will travel about 12 hours and some 500 kilometers through the
desert before arriving in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Hours later, another 30 U.N. staff, mainly senior workers, left
on a U.N. plane sent from Kuwait. (Jordan-UN-Return) 
</P>
</TEXT>
