<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Committed to Peace: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 16 (Xinhua)-- In a response to Israel's
decision to suspend implementation of further redeployment in the
West Bank, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat insisted Monday night
that the Palestinians are committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
The pursuit of peace is the "strategic decision" made by the
Palestinians and should be the same goal for Israel, Arafat was
quoted by Israel Radio as saying.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in the West Bank town of Jerico before
meeting with the United States Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, who
is in the region to oversee the implementation of the
land-for-peace deal signed on October 23.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came hours after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu announced that he would suspend the withdrawal of
Israeli troops from the West Bank until Arafat publicly retracts
the statements vowing to declare independence next May and warning
Israel of possible resumption of Palestinian armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the announcement in a speech opening a two-day
parliament debate over the peace deal under which Israel will
withdraw from another 13 percent of the West Bank in a period of
12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I do not intend to implement any withdrawal under these
circumstance, under the threats that Arafat made yesterday, until
these things are corrected publicly and unequivocally," Netanyahu
said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed his vow Sunday to declare an independent
Palestinian state on May 4 next year and warned Israel that the
Palestinians would take their guns if prevented by Israel from
praying in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat did not directly mention these statements in his
response to Netanyahu's decision.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian news agency Wafa said earlier that
Arafat's statements were "misunderstood." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
