<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-16 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Feels Relieved Over Settlement of Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Spokesman of the Algerian
Foreign Ministry Abdul-Aziz Sab'e on Monday expressed his
country's relief over the peaceful end of the standoff between
Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Iraqi recent decision on the resumption of
cooperation with the U.N. would open new horizons for lifting the
embargo on the brotherly people of Iraq," Sab'e said at a press
conference here.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Iraq agreed to unconditionally resume cooperation
with U.N. weapons inspectors, thus averting a possible military
strike threatened by the U.S. and Britain to force Iraqi
compliance.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian official noted that Algeria always highlighted the
necessity of respecting Iraq's sovereignty and territorial safety
as well as the necessity of integrating Iraq into the Arab family.
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis between Iraq and the U.N. was triggered by
Iraq's decision on October 31 to halt all cooperation with the
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating
weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion
of Kuwait cannot be lifted until UNSCOM verifies that Iraq has
destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Tissue and Bones Bank Set Up in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A first bank of tissue and
bones, necessary for the transplants to the injured with serious
orthopedical illness, is set up recently in Romania at the
Bucharest Central Military Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of this bank is "absolutely necessary since
it can keep up the necessary biological material for the
transplant aiming to resolve the serious injury cases, tumors or
congenital deformities," the national Rompres news agency Monday
quoted the Orthopedics clinic's chief dr. Silviu Diaconescu as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Certain tissues were preserved until now from the patient or his
family members, but some times they did not match or were repelled
by the injured. Now, the people in sufferance could be replaced
large tissues or bones without problems, and the injured could be
saved from cutting off.
</P>
<P>
The donor could be a living person for certain tissues, when
for most of the cases a dead, Diaconescu said, stressing that
donation is made on the basis of an analyses record aiming to
notice the presence of hepatitis B and C, the HIV virus and the
malaria, the nervous degenerative illness or tumors.
</P>
<P>
Biological materials collected up now are sufficient for about
10 transplant operations, Diaconescu added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
