<HEADLINE> Turkey Plans to Abolish Capital Punishment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Justice Ministry has
submitted a motion to abolish capital punishment as part of the
effort to extradite Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan from
Italy.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, the draft law for the lifting of the death
penalty is finished," Justice Minister Hasan Denizkurdu told
reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
The draft will be discussed at the Cabinet meeting later this
week before being presented to the Parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has never executed any criminals since 1984 in spite of
such penalty stipulations in its law.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that this step was taken to convince
Italy, which arrested Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) last week, for using a false passport, that
the rebel leader will not be executed if he is extradited to
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan is accused by Ankara of killing large numbers of
Turkish armymen and innocent civilians since the PKK launched the
separatist war in southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
At present, Turkey is also making diplomatic efforts for the
extradition of Ocalan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
