<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2135GMT, November 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- One Israeli soldier was killed and five others
wounded in south Lebanon Monday by a roadside bomb, the Orient
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was detonated by anti-Israeli Lebanese guerrillas
when an armored Israeli patrol passed by on a road in the Markab
area, in the central sector of the Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
claimed responsibility for the attack, saying one of its units
planted a bomb and killed and wounded all soldiers of an Israeli
patrol. (Lebanon-Israelis-Killed)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In a continuation of war of rhetoric, Israel and
the Palestinians accused each other Monday of hindering the
implementation of the Wye agreement, which has been behind the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu warned Monday that Israel
will not carry out further redeployment in the West Bank if the
Palestinians do not revoke those statements "contradicting" to the
deal, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed a vow on Sunday to declare an independent
Palestinian state on May 4, 1999, when the five-year interim
period under the Oslo accords expires, and warned Israel that "our
rifle is ready."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu responded quickly and sharply Sunday to the
statements, saying they were a declaration of war toward the Oslo
peace process and cast a "very dark shadow" over the Wye agreement.
(Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- "It is about time" to lift the U.N. economic sanctions
on Iraq, visiting Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak on the latest Iraq-U.N. standoff, Sergeyev also
urged progress by the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in its
mission of disarming Iraq of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said Russia is opposed to military solution to the
Iraqi issue, but it also criticizes Baghdad's halt of cooperation
with the UNSCOM. (Egypt-Russia-Defense Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
announced on Monday that he is suspending troops withdrawal from
the West Bank unless the Palestinians retract the statements
declaring independence next May.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking in the Knesset (parliament) at the start of the
two-day debate on the approval of the Wye River agreement signed
with the Palestinians under which Israel will withdraw troops from
13 percent of the West Bank within 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
"I do not intend to implement any withdrawal under these
circumstance, under the threats that Arafat made yesterday, until
these things are corrected publicly and unequivocably," Netanyahu
said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the statements made by Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, who renewed his
vow Sunday to declare an independent Palestinian state on May 4
and warned Israel that the Palestinians would take their guns if
prevented by Israel from praying in Jerusalem.
(Israel-Withdrawal-Suspension)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Thirty United Nations humanitarian workers arrived
here Monday from Amman, Jordan, to resume their work in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. staff, mainly senior workers, flew back from Amman on
a U.N. plane sent from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Another 120 U.N. humanitarian workers, who departured from Amman
on four Iraqi buses, are expected to arrive in Baghdad late Monday
night after travelling some 500 kilometers through the desert.
</P>
<P>
The return came two days after Iraq agreed to unconditionally
resume cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors and the United States
temporally withdrew its military menace. (Jordan-UN-Return)
</P>
</TEXT>
