<HEADLINE> Republican Chairman Warns of Intra-Party Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Republican Party Chairman
Jim Nicholson warned on Monday that a challenge to his leadership
could trigger "turmoil or a bloodbath," and predicted he will be
re-elected despite the party's weak showing in midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Nicholson's detractors continued to discuss the
possibility of a challenger emerging before the Republican
National Committee (RNC) hands out another two-year term in
January. This week's gathering of the Republican Governors
Association (RGA) in Louisiana could test Nicholson's standing.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think in the end anybody will run against me because I
really do have it locked up," Nicholson said in an interview with
The Associated Press. Nicholson said more than two thirds of the
165 RNC members had promised to give him a second term.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's more important to the party than it is to me,
because we have a lot of work to do to get everything put back
together... and also to raise money for the party the next two
months, rather than to deal with any turmoil or a bloodbath that
might result over a fight with leadership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although nobody has challenged Nicholson, several Republicans
have let their names be circulated by his dissenters.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson has tried to secure his position before the RGA
meeting, which begins Wednesday. Several RNC members will attend
the conference, and many governors have expressed disappointment
with Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said he has promised to get governors more
involved in the RNC, both in crafting the Republican message and
representing the party on national television. He also plans
brainstorming sessions among the governors, congressional leaders
and RNC leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
