<HEADLINE> Clinton to Resume Asia Trip This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will fly to Japan and South Korea this week to resume his Asia
trip after the Iraqi crisis was defused, the White House said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at a Wednesday departure," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said at a news briefing. Details will be
announced later, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Clinton will be holding meetings with
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi on Japan's latest stimulus
plan and with South Korean President Kim Dae-jung on a host of
issues including the Korean Peninsula. He will also visit Guam in
the tour.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was scheduled to start the trip with the first leg to
Malaysia to attend an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
leaders meeting. But the first stop was skipped as he was to
monitor the crisis over U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq. Vice
President Al Gore replaced him at the APEC meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president spent the weekend in Washington to focus on
Iraq, announcing Sunday that he had accepted Baghdad's offer to
allow U.N. weapons inspectors to resume their work, effectively
defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that Clinton twice aborted air strikes on
Iraq over the weekend before agreeing to give Baghdad another
chance to comply with the weapons inspections regime set up after
the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
