<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Rally, Dow Above 9,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. stocks rallied Monday
with the Dow Jones industrial average jumping back to the above
9,000 level for the first time in three and half months.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the worldwide stock rallies following the removal
of military confrontation between the U.S. and Iraq over U.N. arms
inspection in Iraq and the announcement of a new economic plan by
the Japanese government, the Dow closed 91.66 higher to 9,011.25.
</P>
<P>
Most of the market indicators also posted gains.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip barometer is still 326.72 points or 3.5 percent
away from its record high of 9,337.97 reached on July 17. The last
time it stayed above 9,000 was July 30. Its recent comeback has
made up over 1,500 points since it plunged to the 7,400 level in
late August amid contagion of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council decided Sunday to send back arms
inspectors to Iraq. A peaceful solution to the crisis sent a
stimulus to markets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Japanese government promised to turn the
recession-bound economy around by next year with a new package of
public spending, also a factor favorable to the business climate.
</P>
<P>
On the New York Stock Exchange, advancers led decliners 7-6
with trading volume up to 610 million shares from 600 million
previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
