<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nerve Abnormality Found to Cause Disabling Rapid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A disabling disease that
causes rapid heartbeat and occurs most often in young women may be
due to a pronounced abnormality in "autonomic" nerve activity --
the body's central control panel for vital life functions like
breathing.
</P>
<P>
Reporting in Monday's Circulation, a journal of the American
Heart Association, scientists say that the disease, called chronic
orthostatic intolerance (COI), is often mistaken for emotional
distress or other medical problems. It has been misdiagnosed as
chronic fatigue syndrome, mitral valve prolapse or panic disorder.
Some patients are referred for psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
According to scientists at Vanderbilt University, the United
States, and the University of Milan, Italy, individuals with COI
lose their balance upon standing and will have a runaway
heartbeat, called tachycardia. These and other symptoms including
dizziness, light-headedness, tunnel vision and general discomfort
can severely disrupt the lives of those with the condition.
</P>
<P>
People with this disorder tend to lie down most of the day, the
report said. As many as 500,000 Americans might suffer to some
degree from the problem.
</P>
<P>
COI is not well defined in medical textbooks and thus its
prevalence is underestimated because physicians don't know how to
deal with the disorder, whose physiological basis is formed by
irregularities in the heart, the scientists said in the report.
</P>
<P>
The scientists found that COI patients have an abnormally high
sympathetic output to their heart and blood vessels, even at rest.
That is potentially related to a central nervous system
abnormality.
</P>
<P>
Typically patients complain that they "can't stand up" -- so
they drastically restrict physical activity, leading to weakened
muscles that only make matters worse. The scientists say that it
is helpful to gradually increase exercise, especially swimming and
other activity in water, where gravity has less impact. Increased
intake of fluids and even small amounts of salt have been shown to
be beneficial, they said. Therapy can also include medications,
such as "alpha 1-receptor agonists, drugs that mimic the body
chemical that helps blood vessels constrict normally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981117.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Plunge with Iraq Strikes Called off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 16 (Xinhua) - World oil prices slided near
10-year lows on Monday after the possibility of U.S air strikes
against Iraq subsided and worries over the glut of global supplies
resurged.
</P>
<P>
On London's International Petroleum Exchange, Brent crude for
January delivery traded 57 cents off at 11.75 US dollars a barrel
after plunging through the psychologically-important level of
12.00 dollars a barrel as the market drew to a close. This was
within 20 cents of a 10-year low of 11.55 dollars reached on
August 11.
</P>
<P>
U.S. light crude for December delivery closed down 77 cents at
12.80 dollars a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
"We have been been bearish all day; the standoff (between Iraq
and the United Nations) is over, the tension is gone, they called
off the strike and they got the (U.N. arms) inspectors back in and
the physical market is weak, so the fundamentals are re-asserting
themselves," a London trader was quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The market has given up the increases in price from early last
week when the crisis was intensifying," John Russel, managing
director of Bangkok-based Petroleum Economics Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts monitoring Iraq crude exports for the United
Nations as part of an oil-for-food program remained in place in
Iraq during the latest crisis and loadings went ahead virtually
uninterrupted, according to shipping sources.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.8 million barrels from Turkey's Mediterranean port
of Ceyhan and 3.4 million barrels from Mina al-Bakr in the Gulf
loaded in the last two days and more loading is now in progress,
Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
But the threat of U.S air strikes stopped some oil loading as
scheduled, the sources said. Bulgaria's Rosbulneft loaded only
400,000 barrels instead of its scheduled 1.9 million barrels,
citing safety concerns for its decision.
</P>
<P>
James Brown, Asia energy analyst at Merrill Lynch, said "I am
not convinced that this present conflict is over. It leaves the
oil market on edge until such a time as this whole question is
resolved."
</P>
<P>
The price slide brings into the spotlight once again high
global oil stocks and efforts by the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) to bolster oil prices, which are more
than 6 dollars lower than levels a year ago.
</P>
<P>
OPEC meets in Vienna next week to decide whether to cut output
further or to try to enforce greater compliance with the existing
cuts and extend their duration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
